Nutrition for children suffering from obesity: No breakfast and no sausage for dinner
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 are overweight; while 9% of schoolchildren are overweight, 5% are obese.
According to a recent study, children who are obese usually come from families that lead unhealthy lifestyles.
We see again the importance of the environment and the patterns of behavior that accompany a person for his or her healthy development.
For example, sausage is nearly twice as likely to be served at the tables of obese children as it is in families with normal-weight children.
More than 19 percent of children with obesity ate fries at dinner the day before the survey, which is part of an educational event called Obesity - This is not a coincidence.
Moreover, families of children with obesity do not exercise, but this is true of most families of modern schoolchildren - only 15 percent of children said that their parents do exercise at least once a week.
The study was conducted on 900 children.
The study was conducted at the end of last school year; it involved nearly 900 elementary school students throughout Bohemia.
The event is held for the second year in a row, with the support of the insurance company Všeobecná zdravotní pojišťovna and the company Unilever.
To date, more than 12 thousand students have joined the project.
Proper nutrition and adequate exercise are the main determinants of the rapidly increasing number of children who are overweight or obese.
"For example, only half of those surveyed said that they ate five meals a day, breakfast-snack-lunch-snack-dinner, which is a requirement of a healthy diet", says one study.
No lunch and sausage in the evenings .
Experts warn that even such relative details as the regular family breakfast time are important for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of school families have breakfast together.
In most families, everyone has a separate breakfast.
The worst discovery was that one in ten families don't eat breakfast at all.
And yet breakfast is the basis of a proper daily diet.
A study found that fried foods were more commonly consumed in families with children who were obese.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sugary soft drinks every day (70%).
Although more than 40 percent of children exercise regularly, that number more than doubles to 15 percent when it comes to their parents.
Make your own menu.
In another part of the study, the selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) were asked to make their own menu based on the foods offered and based on their tastes and preferences.
"The food preferences of Czech children aged 12-15 are far from ideal when it comes to healthy eating".
Their favorite foods include a large variety of flour, meat, and sweet dishes.
"The growing popularity of soft drinks is particularly alarming", says the study's conclusion.
As the main meal, pasta beat the bird by a small margin.
However, the children showed little interest in beans, fish and vegetable dishes.
The Pursuit of a Healthy Lifestyle
The study also found that children are willing to change their eating habits if they are given the right information.
"Many of the control group participants demonstrated a significant shift in preference toward healthy eating when they completed the questionnaire after the lecture. Obesity is not a coincidence", the project concludes.
This was particularly noticeable, for example, in the case of sugary soft drinks, where more children were preferring water.
In addition, the children were more likely to eat poultry and fish as a main dish, limiting the number of sweets and pastries.
A stylist must also be a good psychologist, say professionals
In the first article on stylist training, I lamented the amount of information in the introductory class.
I had no idea what was going to happen next.
Lectures from three experts in the field; advice on how to dress for unconventional figures; and a seminar on how all of this works in real life.
More to come.
The closer we get to the final exam, the more information and practical assignments await us.
The training is every Saturday and Sunday, but it's really packed with information.
This time, with Alenka, the director, (there are no men in the class), we discussed how to dress a woman whose body is not perfectly symmetrical.
Most women are not completely symmetrical.
One has a short neck, another has a boyish figure without proper forms, another weighs more than normal.
The stylist should know how to visually reduce the broad shoulders, lengthen the neck, or add missing volumes.
We were given advice on how to make women like Jennifer Lopez look bigger, with bigger breasts and thighs and a narrower waist, and not dress them too provocatively.
For example, if the waist and thigh gap is so large that you can't find a skirt or pants, you should have at least one custom-made item.
You will certainly not regret the money you have invested, for clothes that fit perfectly are priceless.
You'll feel much better in a custom-made skirt than one that's always moving, rolling, exposing the waist, etc.
The owners of boyish figures, on the other hand, may wear clothes with a row, an applique, a stitch or folds.
Given the abundance of information and the types of figures, I'm glad I have a whole week to figure it all out.
Still, I'm afraid that's a lot, considering the homework we've been given.
Each participant in the course had to come up with two outfits for a celebrity: one for the day and one for the evening.
We have to take into account their modern appearance, their style of dress and the type of figure.
I'm going to dress Miranda Kerr, who you may know from Victoria's Secret advertising campaigns.
I'm happy with myself because her outfit is so much simpler than, say, Britney Spears, or Christina Aguilera, who recently gained a ton of weight (please bear in mind that I'm exaggerating), or a very young Selena Gomez.
We have to cut clothes out of magazines or find them on the Internet, print them out and process them with graphics software.
The mudboard -- that's what we call the result -- then reflects our own style and attitude to the graphic image.
It's important to keep the graphic style component in mind.
The stylist doesn't just dress real people, but creates product pages in magazines (based on specific guidelines, such as fashionable bags, coats, etc.).
That's what the stylist and designer Mario Kamenick was telling us.
But it was only Sunday.
A stylist needs general knowledge
The Saturday lecture, which was filled with information about the types of figures, was animated by three guests who are experts in this field.
The stylist is Honza Pokorny; the fashion designer is Jacob Polanka; and the fashion photographer is Ben Rench.
Jacob reminded us that fashion is an illusion and a stylist should use that fact.
A good stylist can use one item of clothing in different ways.
In this case, diversity is the key to success.
For example, a trench coat can be worn normally, over jeans and T-shirts, like a coat; but it can also be worn on the naked body, without the laces, like a dress.
Another option is to roll up the sleeves or lift the collar, and the whole image changes completely.
"Play with it", he insisted.
However, the advice I appreciated most was this: "For your work, you must know the rules perfectly".
Then you can start breaking them,' Jacob told us.
And I finally understand why we're so obsessed with definitions and rules, what to combine with what and why, when in fashion magazines we often see something completely different.
Not to mention the fashion shows.
I learned from Ben, the photographer, that a stylist should have more options for outfits than he has to take photos.
So for a ten-page fashion review (equivalent to ten outfits), I have to be prepared to create at least fifteen images.
Now I also know that in a picture, an item of clothing often looks and works in combination with others in a way that is not the same as it does in reality.
We have to keep that in mind when we create an image.
Honza Pokorny confirmed that often image and style are half the battle.
Just look at Madonna, who doesn't have a great vocal, but her image and marketing have made her a global star.
Attitudes toward stylists in the Czech Republic are still quite cool.
Even famous people often find it superfluous (and believe that it is enough to be an expert in something, and how they look is secondary).
And if someone finally lets us create their style, we should expect them to tell us a different (smaller) size than the one they're actually wearing.
Then we go to Google and find out if the tabloids have written anything about a celebrity getting fat, losing weight, etc.
On Sunday, Honza and Mario emphasized that it's not enough for a stylist to know fashion and be able to pick out an outfit.
Our job is basically to interact with the people we dress; so it's important to be a good psychologist.
To be able to judge people, not to favor them, and to stick to your opinion.
"If a manager asks you to look at her clothes and add a few pretty things, you can't throw out her entire wardrobe and tell her that her clothes are awful".
"Find at least a few things you can commend, and suggest what you can wear with them", says Mario.
He also showed us what the work bag should specifically fit.
It's a bag that you tie around your waist to carry everything you need.
In addition to obvious items such as scissors, sticky roller or English pins, it should have a nylon thread (stylists use it when shooting some items, such as bags or hats), special clips to attach fabric to the back in case the clothes are too large (shoes and similar items are prohibited, as they spoil the clothes) or a sewing kit.
To distract from the lectures and gain some practical experience, we learned how to make the right shoe soles.
Even when shooting in a studio with a smooth floor, the soles can get damaged - not to mention shooting in the street.
So we started the patch.
You shouldn't touch shoes with scissors, so you don't spoil them.
It takes real skill.
I was glad Mario praised my work.
I didn't like the skills I mentioned.
That's just part of what we heard during the second part of the weekend course.
I'm starting to realize that being a professional stylist isn't easy, no matter what they say.
V Need for Speed: Running is set in America.
The review
What should have been a carefree walk turned into a routine morning commute to work because of a series of completely inappropriate and careless mistakes.
The ambitions were met to some extent, but it didn't matter, because nobody clearly wanted to do the extra work.
Before the release of the new version with the subtitle "Run" there were high hopes.
It was expected to move the previous Need For Speed series in a new direction; demo versions indicated that the game would take its rightful place in the racing game genre.
We were curious to see the parts of the game where the main character gets out of the car and runs.
As is often the case with NFS, the results are very different from what we expected.
The game is a pretty good arcade game, but the general impression is spoiled by a few unnecessary bugs that have been present in this series of games for several years.
So, in reality, these aren't mistakes, but an expression of inexplicable developer laziness.
The adventure starts off very well.
You become part of a story where the main character, Jack, decides to solve some personal problems by participating in an illegal race across America.
You get in a car on the West Coast, in San Francisco, and your job is to be the first to get to New York.
There are some interesting features to this idea.
The route consists of ten stages, divided into more than fifty races.
This means that each race follows its own route, with individual stages taking place in a diverse and interesting environment.
So it doesn't feel like the game is the same all the time.
Although the graphics are at the same level as in previous installments of the series, some of the tracks are enjoyable to watch.
And yet the game doesn't evoke much emotion.
Although driving through the desert, the suburbs in the fall, or high in the snow-capped mountains is a delight.
And the race is occasionally animated by an unusual detail.
For example, in the desert, you get into a sandstorm that greatly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you have to be careful not to get caught in an avalanche.
The individual races are pretty well organized.
There are only a few varieties, but that's enough.
For a while you're trying to outrun several rivals (essentially a normal race); then you're trying to improve your time (a standard race with a stopwatch); or you're competing against one opponent.
And you'll run into the police from time to time, which will make your job even more difficult.
The components on the outside of the car are new.
It's just an interactive animation where Jack is running away from someone most of the time and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right time.
It's not complicated.
Although surprisingly, these fragments are much smaller than you might expect (only three to be exact).
It actually turns out that for a game, that's good because it's not boring; given all of the above, that's one of the things that makes the game more fun.
The racing model follows the tracks of the previous models.
It means that it's no longer something special, but that's not a flaw.
If you're looking for a real-life imitation, you'll have to look elsewhere.
And yet this driving model is very suitable for dynamic racing, although there are better options on the market.
So far, it's been great.
However, after a while, problems arise.
Unlike the driving model, the crash model is not so good.
You don't expect a game like this to be a complex conversion or a collision, but if you don't have a clue before you hit an object about how your car is going to behave, something's wrong.
Usually, when you're overtaking or driving past cars in a traffic jam, you're sometimes touching another car slightly, and yet sometimes in a situation that's almost the same, your car starts to spin wildly.
Or it was broken into pieces.
It's not that important with the restart system, but it's enough to spoil the fun.
The restarts are designed so that if you crash or go far off the track, the game takes you back to where it stopped.
However, only five restarts are available for each race.
If you use them all, you'll have to start the race from the beginning.
It's useful in case something doesn't work, but you can't rely on it completely.
Sometimes restarts aren't enough, and you have to memorize a certain part of the race.
A major drawback of the game is the fact that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns have to be done in a certain way, or you just don't fit in.
In other cases, you'll encounter civilian vehicles in a certain location in the same configuration whether you're first, fifth, five seconds early or a minute late.
This is especially annoying in situations where you see your opponent easily passing between two cars going in opposite directions, when when you're there, the cars are already positioned so you have to either go around them or slow down.
It doesn't matter when you're around them; it's all set up so that the situation is always right in front of your face.
The rivals have other advantages.
During the game, you find several places where, regardless of time, the same opponent is overtaking you in the same place.
This is especially evident at the end of the game, on a long bridge, where you're driving in the opposite direction.
Obviously, your opponent has to stand up to you no matter what.
The thing is, when it's driving in front of you, it's making your view worse, which leads to one or more accidents on that stretch.
You can understand trying to make the game more interesting and adrenaline-fueled, but it's so obvious that it quickly starts to irritate.
It's a shame, because despite the simple driving model, the game is fun and sometimes so eventful that you don't have time to pay attention to what's going on around you.
It doesn't matter what you're not bored with - a concept with fifty unique tracks, a race sequence or something else.
The idea of changing cars during races is unusual.
You need to keep track of the fuel on the way, because that's where your car can be replaced, even though in most cases the one you already have is enough.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are for cities; powerful American cars are for straight highways; and exotic super sports cars are for technical driving, such as on curvy mountain roads.
The main story mode is closely related to the challenge mode; it is races on individual terrains that you learn as you play.
Here you win medals and points for your personal case, common to challenges and story modes.
There are many opportunities to improve driving skills, from cars to profile data.
In addition, the profile is linked to the online feature Autolog, which, among other things, compares your results with those of other players and provides a link to the public.
Here's another flaw that's hard to understand; this is an example from the last race in the sequence.
You and your car are in a subway tunnel (let's assume that) where you're racing down the tracks in the dark (let's assume that).
Your speedometer is showing the numbers from 150 to 200 km/h (let's assume that) when suddenly a subway train is coming at you from behind, turning your car into a pile of metal.
For days, our editorial staff has been debating whether we really didn't think twice about making the game, or whether the creators really think we're such idiots.
The technical aspect of the game is nothing special; but the overall experience of the video series is mostly pleasant, sometimes even amazing.
Although, unfortunately, at some critical moments, the quality of the recording, sometimes quite strongly, declines.
This is especially true in high-stakes cases where a good recording wouldn't help you much either.
The sound is fine; the soundtrack is for amateurs.
To appeal to the widest possible youth audience, the soundtrack 'has been mixed with compositions from different styles'; but it is unlikely that many people will buy the game because of its music.
Overall impression of Need for Speed: The run is rather messy.
If the game had avoided obviously unnecessary mistakes, we could honestly say that Escape is the best part of NFS in the last few years.
Anyway, the game leaves a feeling of incompleteness.
Sure, it's good entertainment, but be prepared for the flaws to blind you like airport lights.
The chorus of the University of Karlovy Vary will perform at the concert "Students in velvet"
For the third year running, the Festa Academia festival proposes to combine the international student day and the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution with a musical event.
He's gonna be performing with about 20 school and university choirs.
The main event of the festival is two concerts, which will take place on November 17.
"The University of Karlovy Vary is actively participating in the festival".
"The participating choirs include the Faculty of Education and Humanities Choir; Vaclav Gampl, the rector, will join the committee", said Yakup Chalon, head of the organizing committee.
The culmination will be a free public concert by the school choirs, which will take place at 2 pm on November 17th on the square in front of the National Technical Library in Daivitz.
The work "Jazz Mass", composed by the famous Czech jazzman Karel Ružička, is also included in the program.
In the evening, the official National House in Vinograd will host the concert "Students in the velvet", with the participation of the choirs of the universities, including the choir of the University of Karlov.
