The main organizer is českých pěveckých sborů (Czech choirs) in cooperation with the Johann Kepler High School.
The whole event is held with the assistance of Boguslav Svoboda, Lord Mayor of Prague, and Vaclav Gambl, rector of the University of Karlovy Vary.
The festival will take place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and Pardubice.
The program offers both official concerts and numerous musical meetings, student happenings, daytime performances, etc.
For more information please visit the festival website: www.festaacademica.cz
Ambassador to the EU Vicenova:
The Czechs have a reputation for being unwelcome and skeptical of the euro.
"The Lisbon Treaty has caused considerable disagreement among individual organizations".
"I didn't expect it to be so brutal".
"It will take five or six years before the situation stabilizes, calms down and all players get used to their new roles", EU Ambassador Milena Vicenova began her lecture at the Faculty of Law with a stern tone.
She demonstrated how true to her motto "Clear and open about Europe" in the very first part of her lecture, where she described the individual EU institutions and the relationship between them in a way that was so simple and clear that many lecturers at KU Law School would have been envious.
Moreover, Vicenova praised the work of the new permanent president of the European Council, Herman Van Rompuy:
"At first, critics said he was just a gray office mouse who couldn't play any role; I have to say, everyone was amazed at how well he handled his role".
"He is a man who can listen to 27 member states at once, who is good at communicating with them and who has a clear idea of where the EU needs to go".
She explained her new position as the EU's foreign and security affairs representative as an answer to the question: "Who is the European Union? What number should I call?"; i.e. as an important step towards unification and greater transparency of the Union's policies towards countries like China or India.
No one's going to ban our cheese.
Vitsenova further focused on the programme that is key for the EU in the past, present and near future.
She called the Czech presidency a success the year before.
The Czechs were dealing with an impending financial crisis; they overcame that crisis and organized the Eastern Partnership summit.
She said that the resignation of the government at the time was a negative phenomenon that caused considerable damage to the Czech Republic.
The Czech representatives in the EU are very busy at the moment.
As the ambassador said, both the presidency and the subsequent financial crisis caused the fermentation that is now ongoing.
And we need to adopt a new seven-year EU budget, which is very difficult given the current crisis.
Whether the budget will be sparse and economical, which areas will be preferred; which countries will receive more support and which less; all these questions are in the upcoming programme.
The Ambassador recalled the key slogans she brought to Brussels: "A Europe in a language that is understood".
"I really don't like abbreviations, foreign words, and jargon that no one understands.
How can citizens understand that in Brussels people are not trying to sell curved or round cucumbers, bananas of different sizes, or that someone is going to ban our cheese varieties.'
It is also going to make more efficient use of the EU environment and attract more Czechs to European organisations.
Europe with high speeds is our future
The ambassador claims that the Czechs are considered eurosceptics; as well as people who point out the negative rather than the positive sides of things.
She wants more Czech representatives to be involved in European organizations.
She believes that this is due to several factors: for example, the modesty of our candidates and their inability to write motivation letters; at the same time with little support from the Czech side.
Along with the successful chairmanship of the Czech Republic, she noted the power and cooperation of the Visegrad Group.
"Believe me, when I meet someone from Poland and Hungary, and we have a Slovak joining us, the Frenchman next to me says, 'Hey, what's the meeting about, the Visegrad group again?' and he's not happy about it one bit.'
In the future, the Union of Vicenov expects mainly new strict rules for the budgetary policy of the member states.
Compared to the new European Federation, it finds the idea of a two-speed, if not a multi-speed Europe, more realistic.
"We have countries both inside and outside the Eurozone".
"We have the Schengen area, and we already have the institute of enhanced cooperation".
"It was said for the first time that countries that want to join should join, while those that don't want to join can stay out".
"The number of such institutions will grow; it will be a truly two-speed Europe", Vitsenova expects.
In this regard, she stressed the role of both the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuy in promoting the rule that all issues affecting the EU as a whole should be discussed by all member states, not just those in the Eurozone.
The history of the brand:
The pioneer IBM is entering its second century.
If someone wants to find a word that best describes IMB's strategy, the closest one is probably "long-term".
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution; the company is considered very modern, although it was founded more than a hundred years ago.
The company's longevity was laid by its first boss, the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He believed in his motto that many of the world's problems could be easily solved if people were willing to think.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the stamp around which the future giant's life revolved (as well as the title of his internal magazine, which IMB began publishing in 1935).
Moreover, it was the foundation of the corporate culture that Watson carefully constructed.
"For us at IBM, long-term thinking means constantly moving forward.
IBM survived and prospered for a hundred years because it remained true to its original values, even though it was not afraid to change everything around it.
In our first hundred years, it has allowed us to transform technology, business and society.
In the next 100 years, we hope to achieve even more", said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company's current CEO, on the occasion of the anniversary.
A complex system
In the 1930s, Watson approached the issue of employee care the same way Batya did in the Czech Republic - IMB employees were among the first American employees with paid leave, employer insurance, elegant uniforms, and a complex system of bonuses for the best inventors and entrepreneurs.
IBM's long-term relationship with consumers is also advanced.
From the very beginning, the company found brilliant applications for talented people, and it was one of the first companies in the world to eliminate all discrimination, giving it a great choice.
It's consistent with the anti-discrimination strategy and the current plan, where a woman, Virginia Rometti, will replace Palmisano next year.
She worked at IBM for thirty years; she is currently the Director of Sales, Marketing and Development.
For the past few years, IBM has been hosting meetings, online brainstorming sessions, where many of the future innovations are being thought out.
It's no wonder there's a lot of ideas -- about half a million people working at the company.
A good organization
A strong position in the business is secured by a strong internal and external image.
"From the beginning, in terms of the concept, IBM was more of an organization than a technology company", said Harvard Business School professor and IBM book author Rosabeth Moss Kanter to The Economist.
"IBM is not a technology company, it is a company that helps solve business problems with technology", adds George Colony of consulting firm Forrester Research.
As the company says, there's a difference between going out and creating a market.
In a hundred years, IBM, or the Blue Giant, as it is known in the United States for its logo, has grown into one of the largest companies in the world.
It seems to be the most versatile technology company -- developing hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consulting services -- from servers to nanotechnology.
It has the most patents of any American technology company, and five of its employees have won the Nobel Prize.
Her inventions include, for example, the ATM, the bank card, the financial swap, the barcode, and the floppy disk.
With $220 billion in market capitalization, IBM this year became the second-largest technology company (first place to Apple), surpassing Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
Looking ahead
Not all of its products were to the taste of the customers and fit the era. For example, IBM failed with its OS/2 operating system, Prodigy online service and IBM PCjr computers.
"If your business is defined by moving forward, you can't be emotionally attached to the past", says Samuel J. Palmisano.
That's why IBM is so quick to build the foundation on multiple platforms -- if they don't work, they abandon them.
This is what differentiates it from, for example, its competitor Microsoft, which is based on and experiencing a downturn on Windows, its operating system.
The future of technology
IBM's main income comes from services, with about one-fifth of each coming from computer software and hardware.
Whereas in 1990, with twice the capital, it was the strongest hardware company.
Since 2000, IBM has sold $15 billion worth of low-yield assets, while investing $58 billion in promising technologies.
It continued to invest even after 2008, when the current economic crisis first hit the world.
IBM is following in the footsteps of its first CEO, Thomas J. Watson, who increased investment during the Great Depression.
So far, IBM seems to have been spared the current crisis.
Since the beginning of 2008, the price of IBM's stock has risen by a record 120 percent; the company's net earnings have been steadily rising.
IBM's corporate motto is to change everything but our own values.
So you can expect that even if another crisis breaks out, this resilient giant will cope.
The story of IBM: from the cheese knife to space flight.
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York City a hundred years ago, and its original name was "Computing, Tabling, Record Corporation", which was a pretty complicated name.
It took the name IBM in 1924, originally used for the company's offices in Canada and South America.
The foundations of the future IBM were laid by the merger of four companies, whose history begins in the 1880s.
They had technologies like the legendary "table clock", which is a clock that records when employees come in and go out of work.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also headed the company's board of trustees.
Flint hired a rival company director, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
Then the CEO pushed the IBM founder into the shadows - Watson's ideas remain the basis of the firm's culture and individuality.
Watson headed the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name implies, started out manufacturing and selling a variety of equipment for the business -- from cheese knives and meat cutters to cash registers.
Within the first four years of Watson's tenure, revenues doubled to $9 million, and the company began a massive expansion across all continents.
Watson became so important to the company that almost forty years later his son, Thomas Watson, Jr., took his place in the chair of the board.
Under his leadership, IBM began developing artificial intelligence technologies and created the first programming language.
In the 1960s, both IBM employees and computers helped NASA control spaceflights to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 the manned flight to the Moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM line System/360.
The classic PC that defined the computer standards of the time, called the IBM 5150, appeared on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer manufacturing to the Chinese company Lenovo, simultaneously buying the consulting division of PricewaterhouseCoopers, thus concentrating entirely on consulting and high value-added services.
Over the last three years, IBM has made great strides with their Smarter Planet concept.
Its aim is to make wise use of technology in areas where it has not yet been planned and to improve road conditions and urban governance.
In the commercial space, IBM recently introduced the Smarter Commerce platform, which helps businessmen control the entire business cycle.
IBM traditions are strong even in our country.
In the former Czechoslovakia, as the first country to be located simultaneously in Central and Eastern Europe, IBM established its branch in 1932.
Today IBM CZ also manages a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe are in Prague, where a world-class research group on speech recognition is also based.
