The price dynamics for travel since 1989
Until 1989, only five state tourist agencies were allowed to operate in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
As travel to the West was strictly restricted, travel agencies of the time mostly sold tours to the countries of the socialist bloc.
Thus, on holidays, Czech tourists went to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, which led to significant restrictions on Czech tourists' travel to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed individual trips to socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel alone, for example to the Soviet Union or Poland, an invitation letter from that country was required; otherwise individual travel was impossible.
At the time, travel agencies offered trips to the West, but you had to either stand in line all night with a sleeping bag or have "good friends" in the agency.
And that wasn't all.
Currency permits were required for travel to the West, and were not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; without a currency permit it was impossible to obtain money (western currency) for a trip to the West.
Most often, the Czechs spent their holidays at home, which led to the appearance of a large number of cottages and summer houses, this custom is preserved to this day.
After 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic experienced a real revolution.
Whereas until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the culmination of our travels, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we no longer realize is that until 1989, we couldn't freely visit what is now the most popular country in Croatia, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
In the early 1990s, the visa requirement for neighboring Western European countries was abolished, and a huge wave of short trips, mainly to Vienna and Germany, began.
The Czechs could not get enough of traveling to the West.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents, as their income at the time was not enough to pay for a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism in that period was the desire to bring their own food (cans, salami, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of the freely convertible Czech krone, which after decades has allowed our tourists to buy Western currencies freely.
Our standard of living and average income were rising, which led to another important circumstance around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has allowed travel agencies to arrange regular flights operated by charter airlines, and flights have become incredibly cheap now thanks to the possibility of ordering wholesale discounts.
By the late 1990s, Czechs didn't need a visa to visit almost all the developed countries of the world except the United States, which made our travel even easier.
The next significant event in the history of travel after the revolution occurred in 2000, when a huge demand led to the first ever direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to the exotic country of Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have taken Czech tourists to warm exotic countries.
Today, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries each year!
And another important event of this period, symbolizing our development after the revolution, happened in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States abolished the visa requirement for Czech tourists, and our country joined the ranks of the world's most developed countries.
For the first time in history, in 2008, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%); and for the first time in history, they spent more than 15 thousand crowns per person during their holiday abroad, including their expenses at the destination.
