She was quick to add each pool she liked to her notebook - with important details about the building's construction and history.
Architectural historian Meder has examined more than 200 swimming pools - and now has gathered her impressions in her recently published book Badefreuden (The Joy of Swimming), which covers everything from public swimming pools in Munich to historic bathing palaces in the Black Forest and "functional concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
Her "journey to the most unusual baths in Central Europe" took her through 13 countries, including Germany, Austria and Switzerland, as well as baths in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania and Poland - and one city each in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old author is a true enthusiast of swimming culture.
She has little enthusiasm for sports, says Mather, but in the water, things are different.
The only drawback is that swimming enthusiasts have to put up with the blue coffee plates and the smell of chlorine, whereas runners can breathe the enticing smell of pine forests or listen to the joyful chirping of birds in the park.
"I once asked myself why swimming pools always have to be so awful", says Meder, who lives in Vienna.
"So I started collecting beautiful pools".
When the surface doubles the architecture
The splashing in the pool and the refined oils in the sauna are so important to the health of the baths because, according to Mader, they stimulate all the senses.
And swimming pools can be a real eye-pleasure if the builders take the time to do it.
"The surface is very transparent, but it also reflects the beauty of the whole building".
Everything is reflected visually: high ceilings, colored tiles and trampolines.
The 190-page illustrated edition of The Joy of Swimming provides valuable information about the architectural and cultural history of health oases - and makes you want to jump in the water.
Collector Meder found several outstanding specimens during her research in Hungary.
She found water rich in nitrates in a karst cave (the Cave Bath in Michkolz-Tapolce) and a thermal bath filled with alkaline water in a building built in the shape of a bottle (Városi Termálfürdö in Jasper), as well as magnificent therapeutic baths such as the 100-year-old Baths of the Secheni in Budapest.
On the other hand, many of the heated outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria offer a spectacular view, you can see the whole of Zurich from a rooftop pool, or you can see the snow-capped Arlberg from an outdoor pool in St. Anton, and there's a steam window that lets you see what's going on at the ski slopes.
Perhaps the most unusual design awaits swimmers in Langenfeld, where the Aqua Cathedral in Öztal looks like a UFO that has just landed in the Alps.
In winter, a pair of three open shells rise from the crater, which appear quite small against the backdrop of the Etztal Mountains.
The Alhambra in the Schwarzwald
Meder, a pool collector, didn't smell chlorine in every pool.
Many thermal baths smell like sulfur, and the Arpad baths in Bekeshchab smell like so much oil that you may find it hard to believe that you are in a healing spring.
The smell is the hydrocarbons in alkaline water, which is almost black from the sludge that sticks to the skin as soon as you dive into the pool, a certain kind of healing experience.
Iris Meder, however, at a certain point became disappointed in her search for beautiful places to swim. When she tried to visit the open pool of the Czech baths in Lugatsovice, she found that the area was sealed.
The baths designed by architect Dushan Yurkovich in 1902 were closed.
When Mather peered into the red-white-yellow windows of the Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds growing between the tiles.
One of the places where the destruction was stopped on hot tracks is the amazing swimming pool in Schwarzwald - the Palace of Thermal Water in Bad Wildbad.
The pools have already gone through three stages of construction, and you'll find not only the neo-Romanesque elements of the period after it was built in 1844, but also the Moorish Alhambra style hall, added around 1900.
After a thorough renovation in 1995, the Thermal Palace is the favorite swimming pool of pool connoisseur Iris Meder - and not just because she is originally from Schwarzwald.
"It's a real achievement to combine so many different architectural styles", says Mather.
Diving into a thermal pool in a palace like this is obviously a secondary activity.
