21st century house in Vienna
Pavilion in a new location
I'm not going to lie.
The Austrian Pavilion for the 1958 World Exhibition in Brussels won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, was empty and abandoned.
Now it's being reopened as an exhibition center.
The Austrian Pavilion, designed by Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 World's Fair in Brussels, is a famous example of modern post-war architecture with its simple forms, glass halls, and boldly expressed belief in technical progress.
The Schwanzer Pavilion won the Grand Prix for architecture in 1958 for its lightweight steel and glass structure.
The building is considered a milestone in modern architecture.
This made the architect so famous that he also built the Austrian pavilion at the next World's Fair.
He eventually became world famous in 1973 with his legendary four-cylinder BMW tower and its sister, the bowl-shaped building.
The pavilion, conceived as a temporary exhibition building, was moved to the Swiss Garden near Vienna's South Station, converted and opened as the 20th Century Museum in 1962 - and is often referred to as the "House of the 20th Century" for this reason.
However, the building was not suitable for the museum for technical and spatial reasons - it had no walls on which to hang artworks, and poor air conditioning.
However, it continued to be used until modern art in Vienna got a new home.
The house had been vacant since 2001 and was in a state of deterioration.
Architect Adolf Krishaniitz has now restored the pavilion, which has been named the "House of the 21st Century" and will be used as a museum of modern art.
This museum is a branch of the Belvedere Museum, which will open its first exhibition on Tuesday evening - in every sense a joyous event.
Agnes Husslane-Arko, who became the new director of the Austrian Belvedere Gallery in 2007, helped to launch the new venture.
Husslyn-Arko, an art history graduate with a brilliant career as a figure skater in her youth, who worked at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and eventually became the founder and director of the Museum of Modern Art in Salzburg, convinced politicians and curators to continue the reconstruction, attracted public funds and private donations, and made a decision on how the building would be used.
The new museum was to house the permanent exhibition of the Fritz Votruba Foundation, a café and a bookstore along with modern art.
Strict control and limited budget
Krushnitz was the perfect candidate to run the project.
He was known, of course, for the restoration and expansion of the Josef Olbrich Vienna Secession, and won the competition, but he also studied with Schwanzer at the Vienna University of Technology, and the pavilion was for him "an extremely important place" where he visited exhibitions "almost every week".
He knew the original design and he knew the challenges that lay ahead of the building, a building that had already lost some of its grandeur and lightness when it was moved to Vienna and transformed.
The problems that arose during the last reconstruction were much more serious.
The window profiles on the glass facade were replaced, glass fiber reinforced safety glass was inserted, and the glass roof was replaced with high-strength safety glass.
The steel overlays of the thermal bridge were reinforced or replaced, and asbestos was removed from the ceilings.
The two lower floors created space for the new use of the building, the overhanging light well between the building and the street provides lighting - a practically new building, but still the elegant Schwanzer pavilion.
The original exterior doors were preserved, and the building was painted in the old red-brown color of corrosion protection.
The cinema hall is the same as it was before.
All this under strict control of the museum's management and with a limited budget.
"We often had to find material that was good, cheap, and would be approved by the museum board", says Krzyszantz, pointing to the uneven floor in the basement.
The building has remained flexible and light despite limitations, problems and transformations.
Krushnitz recently noted that the pavilion "from Brussels" was a rough one - a typical "drop in town" story.
This architecture is "not always in place" and yet it wants to "stimulate real awareness".
The 21st-century house is in a very good place, as the city's planning has been unexpectedly fortunate: a completely redesigned "main station quarter" with offices and residential real estate grows around the Swiss Garden.
A second happy event may occur: the 21st-century house may be supplemented by a second building by Krushnitz - collector Francesca von Habsburg has purchased the Berlin Provisional Exhibition Hall and is reportedly negotiating with the city to place it next door in the Swiss Garden.
