Most of the risk-taking banks in Europe are not in France or Italy, but in Switzerland.
UBS almost went bankrupt during the financial crisis and has been battling one crisis after another ever since.
Now it's up to the German to get it back on track.
Alex Weber probably didn't know he was going to get the part.
In July, after his spectacular departure from the Federal Bank, it was announced that in 2013 he would take up an equally spectacular post as Chairman of the Board of Directors of the largest Swiss bank, UBS; an unexpected and lucrative career move.
Alex Weber was clearly enthusiastic, praising Switzerland for its beauty, UBS for its newfound strength, and made some friendly remarks to his future colleagues.
"UBS has managed to change for the better".
"I look forward to working with Caspar Filliger and Oswald Grubel".
But it was clear in September that things would be different.
A UBS trader in London bypassed the bank's security systems and lost about 1.7 billion euros.
The CEO of UBS, Oswald Gruebel, a banker known not only in Switzerland, had to leave.
Since then, the chairman of UBS has been considered ill, and everyone wants to know: When will Alex Weber finally take office?
Weber has been advising the bank since February 2012.
And, as the bank announced Tuesday, he will take over as chairman in May, not 2013.
This is not going to be easy for Alex Weber.
He's an economics professor and a central bank specialist, not a traditional banker, and he's bound to take some time to adjust.
He was suddenly responsible for the strategy of the bank, which once again proved that it had long since earned the title of "the biggest banking scandal in Europe".
UBS, on the one hand, is very big -- until recently it managed the largest assets in the world -- and on the other, it's been in a scandal for years.
It seems the proud Swiss bank is sparing nothing.
It all started during the financial crisis.
Until 2007, UBS had a great reputation.
The bank combined the image of a stealthy and stable, yet agile asset manager with ambitious goals and a desire to become the largest player in investment banking.
As a result, in 2007, UBS managed $1.6 billion, thus having more money in the hands of wealthy clients than any other bank in the world.
And as an investment bank, it's one of the biggest banks in the world.
That was impressive.
Hans Geiger, a former banker and professor of banking at the Institute of Banking at the University of Zurich, explains: "I always used UBS as a model for a good bank for my students".
"Knowing what we know now, you may ask, "How could I have been so wrong?"
He was really very wrong.
It wasn't until 2007 that it became clear that something was seriously wrong with UBS.
In the middle of the year, CEO Peter Woffley - who was considered a brilliant intellectual and equally brilliant banker - unexpectedly resigned.
A few months later, we were able to guess why he left.
The investment arm of the bank tried to play on substandard securities and was forced to write off billions.
Believe it or not, UBS has announced a capital increase of 13 billion Swiss francs to deal with the crisis.
The bank did manage to find investors -- but investors that many bankers would have politely turned down recently -- one very opaque Asian sovereign wealth fund from Singapore and one Arab sovereign wealth fund so secretive that it wasn't even named.
It was just the first blow.
In April 2008, things got much worse.
The bank had to announce new billions in losses, and the chairman of the board of directors Marcel Ospel - the second-highest-paid chairman of the board of directors in Switzerland in 2006 - resigned.
In October 2008, a disaster struck, and due to lack of investment during the financial crisis, UBS was facing the threat of collapse, and the state had to bail it out.
The National Bank bought toxic securities from UBS for an undisclosed amount of billions, and the Swiss Confederation paid six billion Swiss francs for a convertible bond with mandatory conversion to become co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland was in shock, the country realizing the dramatic consequences of the huge banks that had established themselves in a small country.
After all, the final balance sheet of UBS in 2007 was five times larger than the total production of Switzerland (see graph).
"We can't bail out UBS a second time", says banking analyst Geiger.
The second disaster came shortly after the first.
A few months later, UBS capitulated in a tax dispute with the United States and said it was willing to hand over the data of wealthy clients who may have evaded taxes through the bank.
UBS also agreed to pay $780 million, consisting of unjustified business income and fines.
UBS has thus more or less admitted that it was an instrument of tax evasion.
At the same time, UBS lost what had always been its advantage in the fight for wealthy clients, the veil of secrecy.
After that scandal, Swiss bank secrecy was not what it used to be.
The CEO and the chairman of the board have since resigned, and
The money of the customers began to run out.
In a matter of months, the bank lost confidence in both of its core areas of activity - investing due to failed speculation and managing assets as a result of aiding and abetting tax evasion.
And then it all calmed down and it seemed like UBS had managed to turn the tide, like this scammer-trader disaster, where one trader dropped 1.7 billion euros before the bank realized something was wrong.
One thing's for sure, risk management in investment isn't working yet.
"The Adoboli incident has clearly shown that risk controls have not changed enough", says Martin Janssen, professor of economics and finance at the Swiss Institute of Banking at the University of Zurich.
The chief financial officer of one of the largest German banks is equally confident: "The problem with UBS is that it lacks a tool to control risks".
It was prudence that for a long time made Swiss bankers custodians of the world's largest assets - not unnecessary risk, but safety for money, whether the world had collapsed outside the Alpine republic or not.
The Swiss bank vaults have become a symbol of unwavering reliability, as Lindt and Sprüngli symbolize the refined taste of chocolate.
The UBS headquarters in Zurich still resembles the image of a decent Swiss private bank, only slightly larger.
The layout is a classic in itself.
The bank's head office is located in Zurich on Banhofstrasse, which leads from the main station directly to Lake Zurich, surrounded by the snow caps of the Swiss mountains.
The buildings here are luxurious, and the rents for the shops are among the highest in Europe.
Among the traditional Swiss shops such as Confiserie Sprüngli, there are jewelry firms such as Tiffany's.
Swiss banks have been here for hundreds of years, from the National Bank to the Credit Suisse Palace to elite private banks like Julius Baer.
The heavy door leads to the UBS lobby.
Along the marble-covered walls are large leather sofas, and next to the bank's emblem is a large "Safe" sign.
UBS knows what their customers want, reliability.
But the two biggest Swiss banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, at some point abandoned the Swiss concepts of banking -- or, as the head of one of the smaller Swiss banks believes, betrayed them.
He wouldn't want his name in the paper - like all Swiss bankers, he's also in partnership with two of the biggest banks.
He believes that UBS has become too big - particularly in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons are very active.
He thinks the Swiss have nothing to add.
"And if anything, they've long since adapted to Anglo-Saxon customs".
It was the Anglo-Saxon investment banking that changed UBS, brought it its first big profits and then its failure, and no other financial institution in Europe lost as much money in the jungle of substandard assets as the largest Swiss bank.
The catastrophe became apparent on October 15, 2008.
"That Wednesday, the ruling coalition of a small country of seven million people launched the largest rescue operation in the country's history", writes Lucas Hassig in his book The UBS Crash.
Politicians approved the allocation of 68 billion Swiss francs (about 45 billion euros) to save the bank from bankruptcy.
How did this happen?
If you ask the Swiss banks, they'll say that the problem is mostly the size of UBS.
Two of the three largest Swiss banks merged into one large group in June 1998.
A bank was formed, which was already too big for small Switzerland at the time of the merger, and a bank that continued to grow.
It was also helped by the fact that the two banks that formed UBS were complementary: one was a wealthy but well-established bank specializing in asset management in Zurich; the other was not so wealthy but much more internationalised.
The internationalized investment bankers suddenly had access to a large amount of money that they could use to spin the all-powerful wheel.
Two names are associated with the growth of UBS: Peter Wolffley, the executive director of the UBS group from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, chairman of the board of directors.
"I've always thought that Wolffley and Ospel were the dream team", says banking analyst Hans Geiger.
"Wulfley, a brilliant intellectual, modest and deeply knowledgeable about models and statistics, and Ospel, with his instinct, who has gone all the way up from a bank intern".
But Ospel eventually relied on Woolfley.
"He decided that his models were reality", Geiger says.
"This is tragic".
Maybe it was tragic.
Pride precedes defeat.
UBS employees remember well the board meetings where Woolffley always repeated the same slogan: "Move Goldman Sachs".
The American Bank was the most powerful investment bank in the world.
At the time, he was heading up the "tournament table", which was a record of the banks' successes.
UBS wanted to be at the top of the charts.
He was able to make some of that journey.
UBS was the largest player in the currency and government securities trading.
Authorized management consultants, however, pointed to a weakness: In terms of what is called "fixed income" in banking terminology, UBS was far behind the largest banks.
UBS had a failure in American mortgage products.
To close the hole, UBS embarked on an adventure that nearly cost him his life.
In an effort to grow, the bank and the hedge fund he founded invested in substandard U.S. securities.
It evolved into a large mechanism that consolidated securities based on American mortgages and sold them off -- still taking the risk.
Even when other banks had long been looking for a way out of the process, UBS did not stop.
"UBS bought until the summer of 2007, when the U.S. real estate market was already on fire", says banking analyst Geiger.
The higher the rise, the deeper the fall.
One manager after another had to leave as the efforts to get the bank in order proved to be more difficult than it had initially seemed.
The UBS posts became a child's play with chairs and remain unreliable to this day.
Anyone who leads this huge bank faces a near-impossible challenge.
He has to find a strategy for a bank that has turned its back on all existing business models.
Banking analyst Geiger already has an idea to give up investment banking, focus on asset management and forget about his Swiss roots.
The bank, however, is not (yet) ready to go that far.
