Graches are considered problem birds in many places, and experts today say that these highly intelligent birds will never be driven out of cities.
Some people love birds, others want to get rid of them as soon as possible. Crows have been part of the urban landscape for centuries, but residents are increasingly complaining about dirt and noise in many settlements.
The solution to the bird problem, however, is far from being achieved.
At the first symposium on crows, held in the city of Lér in East Frisia, experts argued that it was no longer possible to drive crows out of cities.
Experts from all over Germany discussed possible solutions.
Searching for alternatives in cities
Conservatives argued that the root of the problem in cities was the migration of the heavily protected grapefruit, pointing out that the use of chemicals in agriculture was increasingly destroying traditional habitat areas.
Hunting, expanding construction, and the cutting down of traditional nesting trees made life difficult for the birds.
The crows are under guard.
In the town of Zest in Westphalia and in the northwest in Yever, Dipholz, Achim near Bremen and Lere there are large colonies, numbering more than 600 parent pairs.
The ambiguous project of shooting crows in Ler caused unfavorable headlines in 2005.
Critics described trapping birds and beating them with sticks as particularly cruel.
"Simple displacement and intimidation are useless", said architect and landscape designer Werner Klever of Ler.
Water-flowing nests or tree-cutting often have unwanted consequences, said Manfred Kaiser, an environmental expert in Lara, Baden-Württemberg.
"The animals are scattered, and the large colonies are divided and spread to other areas".
Scaring is only possible in the exceptional case near hospitals, nursing homes and schools.
"We're going to have to live with them. Getting rid of them is not an option".
The problem in cities will not be solved by separating them from the surrounding areas, says Lera mayor Wolfgang Kellner.
