Mass murder is a human dimension.
Peter Englund's tense and very good new book, Beauty and Sorrow: A Personal History of the First World War, begins with a long list of characters that makes your heart stop.
Here's a tip for reading on: Cut this page carefully and use it as a bookmark.
You will get to know these people very closely as Mr. Englund narrates, and this list of actors will be your GPS, your beacon in those moments when, like one of these men and women, you stray off the road and get lost in the fog of war.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book he's writing now is unusual, he describes it, quite accurately, as "a work on anti-history".
It has few famous names, important treaties, or famous battles; it has almost no ambassadors, clever journalists, or discussions of tactics and military technology.
It is not so much a book about what happened", he explains, "as it is a book about what it was like. It is about "feelings, impressions, experiences and states of mind".
"Beauty and Sorrow" weaves together the experiences of 20 more or less insignificant men and women from both sides of the front lines, from schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and civil servants.
Some of these people are gonna be heroes.
Someone will be captured, lose an arm or a leg, go mad or die.
Their lives here are like church candles, with new ones added to the many others, and some going out at the same time.
Mr. Englund's book is a departure from the standard of historical books.
This is a correction to the idea that World War I was only a heavy trench war on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skillfully gives a panorama of other theaters of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are being attacked by bee hives; one of them is celebrating Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; the unsolved problem is the flies.
It's a very exciting book, almost from the beginning.
War is sweeping over these people's lives like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling like smokeless powder.
When you hear a cannonball in the distance and you're a woman and you're home with the kids, do you stay or do you run?
Anyway, who's next?
Almost no one understands what's going on or why we have to fight this war.
"The lack of facts", observes Mr. Englund, "is filled with guesswork, speculation, hope, fear, obsessive ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors".
"Beauty and Sorrow" follows the fates of people like Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor in the German High Seas Fleet.
Their stories are drawn mostly from memoirs, letters, and other published material.
The stories of their lives may be frightening or exciting, but they are most alive thanks to the small moments and fragments collected by Mr. Englund.
A lot of it is about deprivation and how to deal with it.
He tells the story of a German schoolgirl, and he says, "Erz, Erz everywhere".
"Fake coffee, fake aluminum, fake rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons". What are you doing here?
He keeps talking about Erzac food in Germany.
He describes "meat made from pressed rice boiled in lamb's fat (and decorated with a false bone made of wood); tobacco made from dried roots and dried potato skins; shoes beaten with wood".
He notes that there were "837 registered meat substitutes permitted in the production of sausages, 511 registered coffee substitutes".
Some stories are about honor and courage.
One American observes the urge for cruelty in himself and says of war: "You feel that, after all, that is what men were made for, not to sit in comfortable chairs with cigarettes and whiskey, the evening paper or the best-seller and claim that this show is civilization and that under your stuffed shirt with padding is not a barbarian".
The British soldier, on the other hand, notices that he is likely to die and no one will notice or be upset.
"When a person accepts the idea of self-sacrifice, he would like to think that it would be done in public", he writes.
But it's a lot like "a condemned man being hanged in secret".
Other comments are about the old Europe falling apart and about new kinds of fear.
"Conflict became more and more an economic contest", writes Mr. Englund, "a war of the factories".
He notes the arrival of what he calls "a new face in the bestiary of the new century: a beautifully expressive and ideologically convinced mass murderer in a well-sewn suit who arranges the slaughter at his desk".
People act in unpredictable ways: lowly acts as much as heroism.
Mr. Englund told of soldiers who tried to get venereal disease from prostitutes to avoid serving at the front.
"The most grotesque expression of this can be seen in the trade in gonorrhea dung, which soldiers bought and smeared on their genitals in the hope of getting into a hospital", he writes.
"The desperate rubbed it in his eyes, often leading to lifelong blindness".
Translated from the Swedish by Peter Graves, Mr. Englund's prose is flexible but unpretentious, perfectly suited to his humanistic task.
In dozens of small scenes, he shows how the war "unleashed forces that were completely uncontrollable: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred".
People start asking why their leaders make them go to war.
The best books about World War I were often indirect, like Paul Fassel's The Great War and Modern Memory or such novels as Erich-Maria Remarque's On the Western Front Without Change, rather than exhaustive historical works.
Mr. Englund's book is part of this unusual pantheon.
His book has the most stunning ending I can remember in nonfiction.
I'm not going to tell him.
But it's like he reached out from a book to a page with a list of characters, grabbed it out of your hands and set it on fire with a match.
