Walls have eyes: How researchers study you on Facebook
Before he became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was a regular guy who expressed his anti-immigration views online.
Breivik, who confessed to the July mass murder in Norway that killed 77 people, appeared in his first public trial on Monday.
While Breivik could have acted alone, he was far from alone online: he spent a lot of time preparing for the attack at his computer, communicating with millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the summer tragedy, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how do we find them?
It's easy, you just have to go to Facebook.
"We found that it's not that hard to get at them", says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report on European cyberpopulism by the British research centre DEMOS.
Facebook's personal data pool is so large, Bartlett says, that researchers could easily use the site's advertising tool to pinpoint the right demographic with scientific accuracy - something marketers have been doing for several years.
Bartlett's team found half a million right-wing band fans across Europe and then pitched them an ad, but instead of showing a new band or diet product, the ad offered the user to take a survey that asked about their level of education, their attitude to violence, and their optimism about their own future.
Using Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 members of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without even leaving their offices.
"It's a whole new way of doing research", says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not so surprising: online right-wing groups are mostly young men, dissatisfied with immigration.
But suddenly, "those who combine their online and offline activities are smarter, more democratic and less aggressive than those who just hide behind a monitor".
DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a popular new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers, and political scientists are using the site to study everything from health issues to social trends that are expressed in likes, wall posts, and status updates.
With over 800 million active users, adding an average of three posts a day, Facebook's "super-relevant information" is driving a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the site's title in the title by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you can't reach on the street with a notebook.
"Before, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them".
"You would have to join the party, and they would never accept you", says Bartlett.
"Facebook is eliminating all of that -- you're going to go directly to them".
Others say that the site could be used to identify and research social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their drunken exploits on Facebook were significantly more likely to be alcoholic than students who kept quiet about it.
Moreno suggests that peers of students, such as their dorm tutors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who is too often updating drunk status.
"You can't solve a problem without identifying it", said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior, and Development at the Seattle Children's Research Institute.
"We found a way to identify at-risk children who otherwise would not have been detected".
Facebook also constantly extracts various kinds of data about its users.
The site's data processing team processed statistics on relationship status and Valentine's Day, voter turnout at midterm in 2010, and the National Happiness Index (mostly using information only they have access to - cyberfreedom champions have long insisted that the site should make its vast data collection publicly available for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them whether they like it or not -- in exchange for the chance to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site can process your personal data.
But what if Facebook users become participants in a study they don't even know about?
While researchers have strict rules for doing research offline, online data is publicly available.
"I don't think many users even thought about the possibility that a researcher might be watching their profiles", says Neil Selvin, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study he conducted using publicly available student Facebook pages.
"As far as they knew, it was just between them and their friends".
So the question is, how do we do it?
Even offline, there's no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
On Facebook, it's impossible to know how much of the information in a user's profile and page is true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things", says Selvin.
That's why, despite years of research in technology, Selvin still thinks that the notebook and the pen are the best research tools that we can use.
"There's no substitute for going out into the real world and interacting with real people", he says.
"Social research is supposed to be about social, and most of the social is still offline".
