7 lessons from the lost Steve Jobs interview that's playing in the theater this week
After Steve Jobs' death on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, describing the technical genius as the Great Inventor of Modernity.
But what Apple fans might consider the biggest discovery in the newly discovered interview, which they recalled ahead of the major market previews this week, is how much this creative mind has understood in business processes and manufacturing technology.
He was, of course, a designer, a dreamer, and considered himself a hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and modernizationist of the manufacturing process, who believed that many business leaders suffered from "the sickness of thinking that a really great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] a great idea is separated from a great product by a tremendous amount of skilled labor".
Back in 1995, Bob Kringley was creating the TV series Triumph of the Nerves about the advent of the personal computer, and he spent over an hour with Jobs having a unique, lengthy conversation.
By this time, it had been about 10 years since Jobs was fired from Apple, and he was already working all the way at his new computer company NeXT, waiting for the massive takeover of the Internet.
While a small portion of the Kringley interviews were used in the Nerds, he says the original interviews were lost in transport.
It wasn't until after Jobs' death that the full VHS copy was found in the director's garage.
This footage, slightly edited, is the basis for the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which is coming to Landmark Theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For a man known for his hatred of in-depth interviews, Jobs seems unusually willing to lay out his technology philosophy and business strategy here.
And incredibly thoughtful.
There are four different points in the interview where there are long intervals between questions and answers -- 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts to be precise.
There are also moments when Jobs's perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems irritated by the questions of Cringley, forcing him to move more quickly to issues or phenomena of greater importance.
In the pre-Pixar, iPod and iPhone era, there's something ominously prophetic about Lost Interview, where Jobs evaluates what he sees different companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of information technology.
It's one thing to read about the post-mortem reviews of Jobs, but there's something vulnerable and inspiring about Jobs, who we see here, a troublemaking dreamer on the verge of greatness.
He has a vision of what things could and should be.
Soon after he said it all here, he went and did it.
A brief summary of the seven key findings of the Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"All the time I've been in business, I've been asking, 'Why do you do this?' And the answer you're always getting is, 'Oh, it's just the way it's done.'
Nobody knows why they do what they do, nobody thinks deeply about business.
