How to Catch a Lie
A quick glance at the latest headlines shows just how serious and pervasive deception and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Kane is busy challenging sexual harassment allegations from several women; each side accuses the other of lying.
The University of Pennsylvania administration was charged with perjury for allegedly concealing that a retired football coach had raped boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught on speakerphone telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself by denying his pranks, which were quickly disproved by overwhelming evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign finance fraud involving the concealment of extramarital affairs.
And again, no one who lived through that time will ever forget the media circus with President Bill Clinton being caught lying about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in office.
Stories of cheating on school and college exams are common.
There have been instances where teachers have given students answers to tests to get a good score for their own work.
Teachers who are supposed to teach the opposite are sending a message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How many lies do we face?
In a single day, studies show you can be lied to between 10 and 200 times.
Now it's assumed that a significant portion of this is a lie to save.
Another study found that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting each other.
Lying and lying are skills that everyone needs for both personal and professional purposes.
Unlike a room game, like, say, charades where you have to say, "I got it!" lying detection is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the last six decades at prestigious universities engaged in comprehensive research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One finding of the study is that most of the old myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars look in the eye.
They don't always stutter, stutter, blush, or fuss.
Do not conclude that liars are hard to spot and hard to expose.
An experienced lie-finder can get to the truth by observing the structure of statements, facial expressions, question structure, and temporal characteristics.
I've spent several years researching scientific discoveries in a vast and ever-growing segment of knowledge about lying, and it's clear that lie detection is a modern skill that's easy to learn and that helps you navigate in our complex world -- especially if your professional responsibilities involve recruiting, interviewing, negotiating or managing.
Good liars are excellent at reading others, making them feel at ease, managing their own emotions, and intuitively sensing how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men lie more about themselves, whereas women lie more about others, usually to protect someone's feelings, that married people lie less to their partners than single people do (but the lie they tell is often the most brazen).
We also know that if you're perceived as a liar, others will feel less guilty about cheating you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is called "defining the original state".
This helps provide a starting point for evaluating the changes further.
Observe the posture, the laughter, the voice characteristics of your subject.
You'd better know if a person is always kicking in a normal state, then you won't make unfair accusations when you see kicking in the middle of a meeting.
Then look for groups of deceptive verbal and nonverbal acts.
Treat these groups as red flags, not proof of deception.
Liars can focus on the upper part of their body when they're trying to remember their story, they can put their feet towards the door, lean toward the exit, change their posture in a certain way, or show "post-interview relief" -- this exaggerated sigh of relief and posture change when all the difficult questions are behind them.
Investigators often fake the end of the interview signal just to see that relief after the interview.
So pay attention to the language of your subject.
Scott Peterson is known to have backtracked and used the past to claim that his murdered wife was alive, leading to a nationwide manhunt.
The stalkers may also use distancing in speech, such as "I did not have sexual relations with this woman... Miss Lewinsky", or repeat the difficult question completely.
The most typical verbal indicators are barely perceptible.
Someone might use "qualifying language" when answering a difficult question, "Well... to be honest... as far as I know... as far as I know".
This makes the response more emotional than actual, and is often a red flag.
There is no magic to detecting lies, but you can master the art of cheating.
These skills will increase the chances of everyone avoiding being a victim of skilled swindlers in their professional and personal lives.
