Climate problems have slowed the economy
During the first year of Mario Lopez's rule, Sinaloa saw an increase in unemployment and the illegal labor market, a decline in foreign funding, and a weakening of the economy.
2011 is the year that will go down in Sinaloa's economic history as being associated with the first year of the government of Mario Lopez Valdés, also called the year of change, which generated great hopes for the development of the economy, but given the adverse climatic conditions at the beginning of the year, there was no growth, however, there was a decline in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures in February not only led to millions of dollars in losses for the agricultural sector, but they limited the state economy's growth opportunities, causing economic activity to decline by 3.6 percent overall in the first half of the year, largely due to a historic 31.16 percent drop in agriculture, which affected the dynamics of other sectors of the economy.
According to the report on areas affected by frost provided by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, 835,582 hectares were affected, of which 78.03 percent were affected entirely, and the remaining 21.07 percent were partially affected.
The decline in economic activity caused, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, during the first three quarters there was an accelerated increase in the unemployment rate, from January to March 55,053 residents of Sinaloa were unemployed, with a share of 4.53 percent of the economically active population, in the second quarter the share increased to 5.28 percent, and from July to September it continued to grow to 6.19 percent, the share which in the number of people is more than 74,000 unemployed residents of Sinaloa, which is 18,969 more people compared to the first half.
Liquidity decreases
The unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is overshadowed by many factors, for economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the Autonomous University (UAS), the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, by actions that were taken in public policy.
"What we're seeing now is an increase in unemployment, which is due to several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the marketplace to limit resources imposed by a law that was passed by Congress to fight money laundering, because people who illegally own dollars are not easy to work with, invest and use", he said.
Immigration is suspended
Lopez Cervantes said that there is also a demographic factor in the rise of unemployment.
"The number of people who leave the state to look for work abroad in the U.S. has been limited, firstly because of the difficulty of entry, and secondly because once they enter, they already face a lot of difficulties in finding work, so a group of people stay and demand jobs here in the state, resulting in an increasing unemployment rate", he said.
Violation of formal requirements
Sinaloa's labour market analysis is made worse by the high number of labour violations that prevail in the workplace, with INEGI stating that 60.38 percent of the state's active population work without being listed as workers in any social protection institution.
In addition to unemployment and layoff violations, another reminder of the state's work is its low wages; the state has the lowest salaries in the country, according to records from the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Ministry of Labor and Social Welfare.
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers was 5,352 pesos until September, well below the national average of 7,375 pesos.
FDI reduction
In addition to the decline in economic activity and high unemployment, 2011 saw the largest outflow of foreign direct investment in the last 10 years, according to the Treasury Department, with January-July state FDI totaling $630,697, a drop of 87.74 percent from $5,143,312 during the same period last year.
For its part, the State Government's Ministry of Economic Development recorded only 17,280,000 pesos of investment during the year, which mostly fell on companies in the service sector.
The debt
Amid the economic downturn, the state government asked the state congress in July for approval of a loan of 3 billion pesos to be used for infrastructure projects in 18 municipalities to revive the economy, only 2.600 million pesos were approved locally, and until November, no debt benefits were expected in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For businessmen, the first year of the government of Mario Lopez Valdés demonstrates the lack of government capabilities.
Miguel Loredo Lopez, president of the National Chamber of Manufacturing, said that during 2011 there was a lack of coordination between the wishes of various sectors, including the state government itself.
"The efficiency of the economy in Sinaloa this year was really low, we have to work hard to regain the positions we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, we have not been able to coordinate the efforts of everyone and, above all, the good and synchronized work of the new government team, we hope that next year will be much better", he said.
The slowdown in the economy
Lopez Loredo said events such as the early freezes this year have halted the state's economy and limited its efficiency and growth.
"The low volumes of the economy are the result of several events, including the freeze, one of the main effects was a slow economy that is not getting fast enough to create economic dynamics that allows for an acceptable level of processes, goods and services and therefore at the end of the year we close it below our expectations", he said.
Reviewing the direction
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Mexican Republican Employers in Sinaloa, said the state needed to continue the most dynamic manufacturing activity.
"Overall, we found that we were working on it, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that will redefine the direction and economic course of the state, it is necessary to mobilize all the material and human resources that Sinaloa has", he said.
The work ahead
President Coparmex stressed the importance of defining the future direction to better direct the government's efforts.
"Overall, I would say that the Government is trying to be successful in various areas, in terms of economic development there is little progress, but it is important to develop a long-term program", he said.
He noted that the current administration has demonstrated progress in its own way of conducting public policy.
"There are facts that allow us to say that the government is starting to get involved, and that I can say that some work has been done, and I think the government is realizing that there is still a lot to do", he said.
