The court will approve the "digital television transition" in Mexico in 2015
The shift from analogue to digital is one of the most important changes the world has seen in recent years.
The Supreme Court (SJ) rejected the constitutional claims made by the Senate and House of Representatives against the presidential decree that postpones the so-called "transition to digital television" from 2021 to 2015, as the eight votes needed to cancel it were not collected.
A minority of the four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Mesa, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers by issuing a decree detailing the actions to transition to digital terrestrial television.
As a result, the constitutional claims filed by the Senate were rejected for lack of the qualified majority of eight votes required for the court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in effect.
The draft statement, prepared by Minister Olga Sanchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional because regulating radio and television programming is a right enshrined in law by the Federal Commission on Telecommunications (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and legislative reserve.
Only Salvador, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sanchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
On this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to refute the decree and support the complaints, and Minister Sanchez Cordero suspended the decree and all actions mentioned in it regarding the transition to digital broadcasting.
At the meeting of ministers it was also decided to reject the demand of the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the discussion of the project, also under the responsibility of Minister Sanchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he disagreed with the arguments of the draft in the sense that the federal executive cannot define by general rules the measures to which the state administration should prepare.
"I also don't think if it happened it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body", and reminded that planning public policy in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector has to do with the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate, governing the state.
The replacement of analogue signals with digital ones is one of the most important changes that has happened in recent years, resulting in better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality, and more channels.
Postponing the transition, he said, would mean postponing the benefits of a digital transformation that includes meeting public needs that have more than a technical dimension, "as it covers economic, social, political issues and national security issues".
These issues, he said, "require the work of the whole system, formed on the principle of state economic management, including a group of authorities that the Constitution unites into the state executive".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the transition to digital broadcasting, and have done so with the help of the executive branch, despite the presence of narrowly-specific technical institutions.
It cannot be concluded that the government, by adopting the decree under discussion, which in any case affects the competence of Congress, ensures compliance with the laws passed by the Legislative Assembly in the administrative sphere, he said.
The Michoacan is analyzing the possibility of counting "votes by votes"
According to data transmitted to the PPRV, the difference between first and second place in the gubernatorial election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes, which are 879 out of a total of 6,074 protocols.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is real with respect to this year's election process in Michoacán, where, according to data obtained from the Preliminary Election Results Program (PPRV), the difference between first and second place in the gubernatorial election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes that come to 879 out of a total of 6,074 minutes.
In light of this, the chair of the General Council of the Michoacán Electoral Institute (IMI), Maria de Los Angeles Lyandreal Saragossa, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral corps approved a package of principles to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
It should be recalled that Michoacán did not adopt the Constitution or the State Electoral Code or the Voting Rights Act, as the state Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their entry into force in this electoral process and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel did not include its publication within the deadlines set by the law in the State Official Gazette, stating that he had some objections.
On the same day, November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice (SJC) ruled on a constitutional claim by a local legislature, and called the state representative's vote on constitutional reform "invalid and illegal" because he had no right to "allow or support them".
In an interview about the possibility of "vote after vote", Maria de los Angeles Lyanderal argued that with the adoption of appropriate principles by the General Council of the IMC it would become possible to submit a partial or complete count of votes to the local electoral body.
For example, a partial recount of one or more ballot boxes may be made if: the results of the minutes do not match; there is no voting and counting record in the ballot box or it is not with the chairman; or when there are obvious errors or corrections in the record.
Furthermore, a general recount of votes in all ballot boxes in an election may take place when there is an indication that the difference between the presumed winner of the election under consideration and the second-place candidate in the vote is less than or equal to one percent, provided that at the beginning of the session there is a request from the representative of the party and/or coalition that put forward the second of the mentioned candidates.
A total recount will also be made if at the end of the normal counting it is established that the difference between the winner and the candidate who came second is less than or equal to one percent, provided that there is a request from the political party whose candidate came second, in case the ballot boxes that were taken into account in the partial recount are excluded.
It is worth noting that in this situation are the elections in Morelia, where, according to the PPRV, the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, not even counting 129 votes out of the total number of 923 protocols.
His last will and testament
His ashes will be scattered in the Sappana Mountains, the family confirms.
The remains of pilot Felipe Basio Cortés arrived in Saltillo, his hometown, on Sunday evening; a funeral mass was held Monday.
According to the family, the last will of the lieutenant colonel was that his ashes be scattered in the Sappalinama Mountains.
After accepting condolences along with others who died in the crash, the Bassio Cortes family returned to the capital of Coahuila aboard a Mexican Air Force aircraft, with the closest people attending the ceremony in Campo Marta.
At noon, the lieutenant colonel arrived at the chapel on Nazario Ortiz Garcia Boulevard, where his family and friends were arriving.
At 5:30 p.m. he passed the Santillo Institute of Technology examination, organized by his former high school classmates and the football team, of which Felipe Basio was a member during his high school years.
"He wanted to return to Saltillo and have his ashes scattered in the Sapariname mountains, and he always told his family and friends", reported Sandra Cortes Basio, the pilot's sister.
In her opinion, the lieutenant colonel fulfilled all her dreams, she believes that he was at the peak of his life, "he was a successful man, an incredible father, son and loving brother, devoted to his family".
Felipe Cortes Basio left the city of Saltillo at a very young age to enroll in the Aviation College in Sappano, Jalisco.
Some people didn't believe him, they said he was dizzy even in a truck, but he always wanted to fulfill his dream of becoming a pilot.
His nephew Jorge Alberto Davila Basio remembers him as a very good man, "as soon as he arrived in Saltillo the whole family wanted to welcome him, like when he brought Marta Saagún to Saltillo".
The young man recalls that even when he was seven years old, he went to Sapporo for his cousin's graduation ceremony, so he knows that his uncle died doing what he loved most in life: flying a plane.
He's being escorted to the last road.
Gunfire rang out in honor of the Mexican Air Force lieutenant colonel Felipe Cortes Basio, led by Governor Jorge Torres Lopez, people from the village and the state government, the Mexican Army, from the Sixth Military Zone, the Mexican Air Force itself, the leaders and students of the Saltillo High School of Technology, where he studied in 1985 and made success in both studies and sports, guided him to his last journey.
Basio Cortés died recently when the helicopter he was piloting crashed, along with the Secretary of the Provincial Government, José Francisco Blake Mora, and six others, all representatives of that ministry.
At 6:05 p.m., the remains of Basío Cortés (cremated), a Saltillo resident, arrived to be delivered by the funeral home to members of the Mexican Air Force led by Major James Martínez, on the grounds of the training school, where he was already awaiting his family, including his daughter Amanda and his wife Cristina, her mother, brothers and other relatives, students and teachers.
