The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The newly appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to introduce a new government that will face the crisis that has brought the country to the brink of economic disaster.
The newly appointed Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the Italian President on Wednesday to introduce a new government that will face the crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic disaster and has damaged the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace said that Monte, appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he could form a government.
He is expected to introduce a cabinet made up mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive branch will take its place.
Monti said he would present the president with the results of his negotiations with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to reaffirm my full confidence in our country's ability to get through this difficult period", the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monty did not say directly that he was able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that the obstacles had been overcome.
"The structure is well-defined now", he said.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, which is much less than usual, as Italy struggled with a political and financial crisis that brought their debt levels to a critical level.
The administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve the austerity package demanded by European leaders to restore confidence in Italy.
Under pressure from the volatile markets, Monti was forced to rush Italy's 10-year BTP yield to above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to be bailed out.
Emma Marchegalia, leader of the Italian Federation of Employers, told reporters after meeting with Monte: "We said we would actively support this government".
We believe that this government is Italy's last chance to get out of this critical situation.
Monti's chances of success were largely based on the support of the LDP party of Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday due to the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts should lead to a good outcome", Angelino Alfano, the secretary of the centre-right party, told reporters.
The support of the LDP, the largest party in Italy, is significant because until now many of its members have opposed the government majority of technocrats that Monti is forming.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to carry out reforms that are likely to be unpopular with austerity reforms.
Any blocking or suspension of these attempts could lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has stepped up pressure, warning that Monte's failure could be a disaster.
Monti began his consultations on Monday with political parties, unions and business groups, as well as youth and women's organizations.
He'll finish his rounds Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who authorized an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief hiatus late last week when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, the value of Italy's debt has now reached a critical level amid uncertainty over whether the new prime minister will be successful.
Bailing out Italy with a public debt of 1.8 billion euros would be too much for the modern financial protectors of the eurozone.
Monti said his government would exist until the next election scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians would only give him time to carry out reforms before calling new elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the main parties insist it should be made up of only technical experts, a sign of their dissatisfaction that the process is affected by the financial situation.
Political sources reported that the mutual distrust and disagreement between the parties complicated the attempt to include political figures.
