The quintet has embarked on a tour to mark the 20th anniversary of their career.
A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true.'
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to give one of their best gigs next Sunday at National Stadium.
It's been over 20 years of waiting, but the band says it's also a dream come true for them to play in this country.
That was the claim of bassist and founder Jeff Ament, who gave an exclusive interview to Viva from Brazil last week.
The band is in South America as part of a twentieth anniversary tour and will make their only stop in Central America on Sunday, the 20th.
They will perform at the National Stadium starting at 7:30 p.m. with the Los Angeles team The X and local band Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the interview, the full transcript of which is available online at The Nation.
For your fans in Costa Rica, is it a dream come true that Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica?
A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is only our second visit to South and Central America, and so far, everything is going well.
I've only been to Costa Rica once - on vacation, it's a beautiful country, and I think we can stay there for a few days.
So we're really excited to bring our music there.
I ask this because there's a certain amount of loyalty to the band; fans live in tension in the days leading up to the show.
What would you say to your most loyal fans?
Thank you for being with us all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica, thank you for waiting so long, and we're sorry it took us so long to get here.
Some people, in anticipation of your concert, are treating it as the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a little tension to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we've played in the last 21 years have been in the last two weeks.
We've done some great shows in São Paulo and we hope that it's gotten us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really want to play here.
We love this country, we love surfing and the jungle, and when it comes to those two things, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you learn about Costa Rica and its surf waves?
We have a lot of surfer friends, and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo, and the waves here are amazing.
My friends go surfing all the time in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, and Mexico, which are great places to surf, and that's how we learned about it, from people who love surfing.
Looking at the tour, you've done some great shows with a lot of songs.
What are your plans for the Costa Rica show?
Since we've never played there before, we have no limitations on what we can do.
We're going to try to do the best show we can with the most diverse songs; we're going to try to play a few songs from each album and present our fans with the most diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
How does that happen?
I think part of it is because we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs, and everyone likes different songs, so it's hard to pick which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs that we haven't played in a while, it keeps us in tune and surprises us, because it reminds us of the reasons why we loved those songs and what we might have forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting for us and therefore, I think, makes it more interesting for people.
This tour is your 20th year in the business.
Looking back, it's hard to believe all the things you've done?
Yes, of course.
First of all, I don't think either of us ever imagined that we'd be in a rock band, and the fact that we've been doing this for over 20 years makes it seem like a dream.
We're happy with our luck and we're very excited that we can continue to make music together.
We all love each other and we all love making music.
We're happy to travel to places in the world we've always wanted to go.
Things are going really well for us.
What does it mean to you to be a significant part of the grunge boom?
It's always been an honor to be part of this group of great collectives.
We're good friends with the guys from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It's great when a movement grows out of a group of friends, and that's unusual.
Every once in a while, one group from one city shows up, but it's much stranger when five or ten groups show up at the same time in one city.
We're proud and honored to be part of a group from Seattle.
I still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we were at the Alice in Chains festival and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, and we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we're happy to be friends with all of them and we're honored to be part of the Seattle sound that's come out.
It's also very strange that a band like yours has stayed together and in the same line-up for so long.
Yeah, the four of us have been together 21 years, and Matt joined us 13 years ago, which is way longer than most bands have been.
First, I think we're lucky to be alive, and second, we care about others.
We're all very close friends, and because of that, there were also musical avenues that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other's music, and it couldn't be better.
Your attitude to the word glory was not easy; but thanks to your success you were able to do everything you wanted to do.
How do you find the balance?
As we got older, it became easier to find balance.
We make sure we don't stay on tour too long, because it's easy to get into this game with big crowds and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are here for music, it reminds you that you have to respect music and what it's made of, not deciding to be famous and be a rock star, which is something that none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other project, Manother Love Bone?
I think we're writing really good songs and it was great at the beginning.
We were together for almost three years and didn't release an album until Andy died.
There were a lot of disappointments because it's been so long, and the most important thing is that we're still close friends with Bruce and Greg, who started with us in the band, and when I hear a song or see a picture, I think about the incredible person that Andy was, and how he made me laugh, it was always fun to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football and so much more.
He was a wonderful man, and we miss him.
The local band Las Robertas will be responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you're familiar with her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose her to open?
Yeah, the producers sent us a couple of video suggestions, and it was the band we liked the most, so we're really excited to see what Las Robertas can offer live, and it should be really exciting.
Why do you always change the lyrics to Yellow Ledbetter at concerts?
It's a question for Ed, so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he uses the first thing that comes into his head.
Who influenced you as a bassist?
There's so many of them.
Among the first to come to mind are Geiser Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramon, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Duckowski...
There's so many I could talk all day about the bass players I love.
How did Pearl Jam succeed in keeping the grunge out of the way when it was no longer in fashion?
I think we all feel a little bit detached from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of bands that I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana, and all the other bands that came out at the same time, and if it's important now, I think it's great, because it's music that's worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are making music better now than ever.
Your music was more gloomy at first, but now it's more positive.
How would you explain this change?
It's interesting because I think there are a few songs on the album that might seem easier, but there are songs like The End or Just Breathe that are considered very dark, although they may sound a little bit positive.
Both of them, when Ed played them, I cried when I listened to them, these songs are very dark.
I think that when you're growing up, and you've had some trauma in your life and you've lost a family member or a friend, those events start to affect your creativity and your music, and these two songs, of course, reflect that for me.
So I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make dark music.
