Fuhimori was hospitalized again for medical examination
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized Tuesday at a state hospital for a physical examination for the loss of muscle strength that he has seen in his legs, his family doctor said.
Fuhimori, 72, who was sentenced to 25 years in prison for human rights abuses committed during his rule (1990-2000), suffers from several diseases, including tongue cancer, for which he has undergone four surgeries and is under observation.
Congressman Alejandro Aginaga, who is his personal physician, told N TV that Fujimori will be examined in three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the cause of the pain and loss of strength in his lower extremities.
Aginag said that he thought Fuhimori should be a candidate for the benefit of a pardon for humanitarian reasons; however, he said he did not want this because he knows he is innocent.
He had undergone four surgeries for tongue cancer, lost 30 pounds [18 kg], and had other ailments, such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cysts, kidney stones, high blood pressure, and leg circulation problems, the doctor said.
Fuhimori has been in prison since September 2007, in the National Police Special Operations Directorate.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the forces of the army extermination squad, which operated in secret during the early years of his rule.
Mujica is going to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and comprising several ministers and businessmen will arrive this Tuesday with a visit to Mexico to expand trade between the two countries and to begin negotiations on political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, the most important item in a comprehensive plan to meet with political, business and community leaders in Mexico, according to a schedule released by Uruguay's leadership.
The two presidents' meeting in Guadalajara will be "a good opportunity to exchange information on the political relations between the two nations", the South American country's leadership said on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking Calderon's support for Uruguay in the incident with France, which occurred when French President Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country on the list of tax havens at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
