Park or mountain?
Architects agree to contest after disputes over dues
Municipal contest for 16 doors renewed debate on the role of Colcerola in Barcelona
In the mid-80s, during the rise of the now-defunct Capital Corporation of Barcelona (SCB), this administration printed promotional leaflets for Colserollas.
The booklet described the mountain as a large park in the capital city of Barcelona.
Moreover, it was accompanied by a comparison in the pictures with Central Park in New York.
With the death of the SCB, in 1987 the park once again took its place in the minds of many as the highest point of Barcelona as the capital of Catalonia, one of the few that is not oriented to the north-south, but up (mountain) -down (sea).
The positioning of Colserola as a nature park is contrary to this idea.
The prototype was not Central Park, but Yellowstone, with the wild boar as Yogi Bear.
This was until, in September, the council announced a huge competition consisting of 16 contests for many other gates in Colcerol.
The gates are the idea of the park, no doubt.
Either that or someone wants to put a goal on the field.
The question is, is it a park or a mountain?
The competition, and its organizational aspect, and its impact on the city, are a topic for discussion by all the architects of Barcelona.
This is probably the most common theme discussed when two members of this elite clan meet in an elevator.
And this fact leads to one of the few coincidences between what the three architects in Barcelona are saying and the scientists who were there.
Miguel Roldan, Daniel Modolo and Mara Bayona: the competition is appropriate
For Roldán, after reaching the coastline it becomes "necessary" to discuss the "front side of the mountain" when the proposal of Ildephon Serda, the mountain with the green apples, was not implemented.
"It must be admitted that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things, it's very accessible.
The Colserollas are more complex", says the architect, for whom the title "Colserollas Gate" contains a "verbal trap": we should not think of them "as an entrance to the park, but as a limitation of some areas where we have to act".
Modolo, like Roldán and Bayona with experience in urban planning, called the proposal an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers".
The risks arising from the "uncertainty of predicting public space" after the experience of the 80s, which ended on the Forum site "with its own swan song".
The first fear is actually the limitation of the boundaries that we can build.
"Limiting something is preparing for the next step", meaning transition.
"We have to think about new urban planning tools because the current ones [as far as the Capital Master Plan (CMP) is concerned] can lead to real trouble".
More to the point, Modolo believes that the simplification of the Colserola Valley "can be understood as a park, Barcelona, not" as a purely topographical issue.
Modolo recalls that there is already work being done outside of Kalserola, which "should not be overlooked", although he is grateful for the opportunity the city offers his profession to join this project "from the beginning".
Moreover, he understands that the proximity of the mountain to the city is a pass that allows architects to enter into a debate, but "he doubts" whether this technical profile is what should guide the interdisciplinary teams ("success", he argues) that were supposed to create: "Architects should be only a tool".
Bayona hints that the answer to the question that gives the title to this piece is complex, since the rules of the competition lack the general view of the Colcerola: "There were announced 16 intersecting contests", he says, "in the sense of sea-mountain, but there is no longitudinal reading to see and understand the area as a whole".
That makes him, at least in his case, decide to enter 16 contests.
On the other hand, a design for one gate may intersect, by program and definition, with an architect's design for a neighboring gate.
From your point of view, the council must ensure that the strip directly above the Ronde de Dalt provides a complete area equipped to create a smooth transition between the city and the greenery.
