MSS announces the obesity gene search program
Social Protection is leading a study to find the gene for obesity in children and young people; it is supported by specialists from IPN
The Mexican Social Security Institute (MSSI) announced that it is conducting a study to detect the gene of obesity in children and young adults, which has been called the "Childhood and Adolescent Obesity Genetics Protocol", which will provide a count of the signs associated with being overweight.
In his statement, Miguel Cruz Lopez, head of the Biochemistry Division of the Specialized Hospital of the National Medical Center of the XXI Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, dietitians and social workers had been assembled.
The team is assisted by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Health (NIPH) and the Center for Scientific Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
The public, whether prescribed or not, is invited to participate by visiting participating MSSI sports centers in the Valley of Mexico, where testing will be conducted with children every Saturday morning at 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol was started at the sports center in Cuauhtémoc (in the west of Mexico City), and since October 8 the events have been held at the sports center in Nesahualco (east of Mexico City).
After the goal of 500 to 600 children is reached, the study will continue at Independence Sports Center (south of Mexico City) and finally at Morelos Sports Center (north of Mexico City).
He explained that the goal of this study was to understand the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to establish a risk factor among children and adolescents in Mexico to prevent the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
November 14 will be World Diabetes Day, and the main goal is to gather three thousand children and adolescents aged 6 to 14 with the permission and supervision of their parents to fill out individual nutrition questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases to avoid risk factors that lead to diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that Saturday will be anthropometric measurements of all participants (weight, height and waist span), measurement of blood pressure and glucose, fat, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetic analysis (to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz Lopez said the study reflects the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain among children.
Medical studies conducted between 1999 and 2006 show that in just 6 years, there was an increase: 77 percent of boys were obese, 47 percent of girls; and there was a significant increase in overweight", said the MSSI specialist.
He said the rationale for searching for markers was based on the fact that the country's population is different from other peoples in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican is 65 percent American Indian, 30 percent European, and five percent African, and that condition has been reflected in genes that are associated with diabetes and obesity.
He explained that obesity is largely a genetic result of the body's inability to burn the excess energy we consume, and it is stored as fat.
The immediate benefit, the researcher explained, was that the children were given a comprehensive assessment that could reveal whether they were overweight or obese.
Even, he said, the presence of dark folds on the neck and forearms indicates the possibility of metabolic disorders and even prediabetes.
The information is treated with all confidentiality, the doctors give it in writing to the parents, and they explain to them all the dimensions and lifestyle changes that must be made to avoid the disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main causes of overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: sedentary lifestyle, or lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day at home in front of the TV, and using short distances of transportation instead of walking.
This is also due to high calorie intake, i.e. increased consumption of sugary drinks and carbohydrates (tamale, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and genetic predisposition, analyzed in this program.
UNAM asphalt will be able to avoid cracks
Raphael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM chemistry department, has developed a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of the highest quality, resistant to environmental and temperature impacts.
If the signals sent by the road surface were taken into account, about 200,000 holes would need to be repaired each rainy season in the metropolitan area of the Valley of Mexico, says Rafael Herrera Najera, a researcher at the UNAM chemistry department, adding that if the process of building and maintaining the paved road surface is correct, the number of holes could be reduced or even reduced to zero.
In his lecture Technological View of Pits, delivered as part of the International Year of Chemistry, it is reported that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing a polymer-modified bitumen for the production of a mixture with characteristics similar to bitumen, but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nahera said that this type of modified bitumen could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and therefore prevent pit formation.
He explained that bitumen, the heaviest part of oil, is a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, one of high molecular weight called asphaltene and the other of low molecular weight called malten, which together give the road surface its characteristic viscous elastic behavior.
The viscous behavior of bitumen is that at high temperatures of about 180 degrees it behaves like a liquid, at 120 it is very viscous, and at 50 degrees Celsius it remains almost solid, while at very low temperatures it becomes brittle, he said.
This means that the resistance of street asphalt is not constant, but changes during the day, depending on natural conditions and temperature, said a chemical engineer.
The chemistry scientist noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered with a flexible coating, which is made up of six layers of material, the last three of which include bitumen.
Among the uppermost layers is bitumen, which is made up of small stones that are lowered into the bitumen and then pressed.
Every stone that makes up this coating, he said, is dipped in bitumen.
When vehicles are moving and putting in effort, it helps the forces to be very well distributed across the road surface.
If it were modified asphalt, they would be even better distributed, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt surface, he added, there is a last layer, which is called the wear layer, which is made of fine stone, actually sand also submerged in the asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will contact the wheels of the vehicle, it must have greater resistance than the asphalt surface and provide road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and distribute the applied forces, the wear layer also requires proper thickness, and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are also very important factors to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the condition of the asphalt.
When the soil is wet, water enters the coating and it is difficult for it to get out, this causes the softening of all the coating layers and therefore the formation of pits.
When a pit is formed, he said, the first thing is the wear and tear layer and then it affects the bitumen, but the damage doesn't happen instantly, which is a process that should be taken into account at the first signs of ongoing repair programs.
The member of the National Research System also explained that the transport load is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each coating layer should always be related to the transport load and it is necessary to guarantee the fulfillment of this requirement to prevent the frequent appearance of holes.
Raphael Herrera said that there was still much to be done about bitumen, and that bitumen emulsions, for example, were already on the market in other countries and even helped to repair pits easily and without using high temperatures.
