That was the work of the man who identified Alfonso Cano's body.
The Cali forensic scientist went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of Alfonso Cano.
The work of these employees is key.
On November 4, CTI forensic scientist Cali made history as the person who confirmed the identity of FARC leader Alfonso Cano by matching his fingerprints.
Seven forensic scientists working at CTI are on duty this week to investigate Eleazar Gonzalez, a man from Puerto Tejada who has spent 21 years in the field of forensic investigation.
Early in his career, Gonzalez worked in the cities of Choco, where he often had to travel more than five days through the jungle to reach the location of bodies that needed to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the Valley and after completing the corresponding courses he became a specialist in the field of criminology, where he studied the friction of the skin, i.e. palms and soles.
During the week of Elizardo's operation to identify the man known as Alfonso Cano, he was told to wear clothes for no more than three days.
Something big was coming.
He flew in from Kauka to Palmyra on Friday night.
He knew he'd have to identify two bodies, and one of them was supposed to belong to the man who led the world's oldest guerrilla war, so they asked him to take ten pictures of the fingerprints of Guillermo León Saenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the research team at the site of the body, he did not identify it by its appearance; it was very different from what was shown in the media.
He was beardless, dressed like a local farmer, without glasses, and considerably thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
Using magnifying glass, ink, a shovel, and a flashlight, Eliezer matched the body's fingerprints to those in the photographs.
His eyes did not disappoint: it was Alfonso Cano.
That same night, a representative of Puerto Tejada was asked to confirm to Defense Minister Juan Carlos Pinson that it was the head of the RVSC.
Fingerprint searching is now complete .
For the specialist in dactyloscopy of the Sijin unit from Cali, the recognition received from President Juan Manuel Santos by Elizaro González at a press conference on the operation against Cano is particularly significant.
A lot of people don't know what we do.
Dactyloscopy is a rigorous, error-free science, and it can play a key role in solving crimes.
In addition to identifying bodies, fingerprint specialists are involved in the investigation of crimes such as theft and murder, and they identify those arrested.
Many criminals are caught with fake IDs or no IDs.
We're taking their prints and running them through the database.
The investigator said that in the case of theft, he had to remove a piece of the wall of the house because that was where the thief leaned his hands to get hold of a safe full of jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult to work with because they are not a convenient surface for fingerprinting, but in this case we can take a picture of the entire palm and identify the criminal who participated in several thefts", he says.
