The introduction of the "golden rule" of the budget into the constitution
The leadership of Austria's ruling Social Democrats and Christian Democrats grand coalition decided on Tuesday to write a budgetary "golden rule" into the constitution to reduce the budget deficit and thus avoid a possible downgrade by rating agencies of Austria's state credit rating (triple A).
The Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Feymann personally announced this decision at the end of the Council of Ministers, despite the fact that Austria's public debt is 74.6%, which is significantly higher than the upper threshold of 60%, established by the Maastricht Treaty, but lower than the public debt of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
If Austria's ability to pay had fallen by just one point, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay interest by three thousand million euros more every year, argued Christian Democrat Vice Chancellor and Foreign Minister Michael Spindelleger.
Austria is thus fulfilling the demand of the summit of Eurozone member states on 26 October in Brussels; the heads of state and government demanded a reduction in budget deficits by the end of 2012 and a return to balanced public accounts through a constitution or equivalent law.
The Austrian government's decision is reminiscent of the "German model", since Germany was the first European country to adopt this "rule".
Until 2017, the structural deficit of the state budget should be reduced every year by 0.75% of the gross domestic product (GDP), and from 2017 the structural deficit of the state budget of the federal state in any year should not exceed 0.35% of the GDP, and lands, like communes, should represent balanced budgets.
The goal is to bring the public debt below the 60% mark, as enshrined in the Maastricht Treaty, by 2020/2021.
