Energy policy:
Facts must prevail over dogmas
If there is one issue that cannot be decided after a brief discussion or under the influence of emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is a healthy trend that election meetings become a reason to think about the role and place of nuclear energy.
The debate will not bear fruit until all the economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options are explored.
France must base its opinion on objective facts and rational data.
We're seven billion people on the planet right now, and demographic growth will double our electricity needs by 2050 unless a huge portion of the world's population is deprived of the elements that are vital to life.
During the same period, it will be necessary to fill the growing fossil resource gap to continue producing electricity on a continuous basis, while also keeping in mind the critical need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate imbalance, a topic that has disappeared from the environmental debate.
The Fukushima accident doesn't change any of those things.
That's why Germany is left alone in its decision to abandon nuclear energy.
This is not the case of Belgium, which has made its decision dependent on the need to find a source of energy that can replace nuclear energy, or Switzerland, which has decided to build only the most modern reactors.
On the other hand, the United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil - these are just a few of the countries that are determined to continue their projects.
The United States decided to add one more unit to its fleet after Fukushima, resuming construction of the station that had been interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
Although the German renewable energy model is sometimes cited as an example, the reality contradicts this argument.
The choice of Berlin would result in increased electricity costs, increased energy dependence, exacerbated by the increased demand for imported gas, particularly from Russia, and a jump in carbon dioxide emissions due to the construction of gas and coal stations.
In a few months, all these unpleasant effects will be felt.
We should consider the example of Denmark.
Europe's champion in turbine construction, from which it gets 30% of its electricity, it is also the largest consumer of coal and gas due to intermittent wind; which causes carbon dioxide emissions and electricity prices to be 65% and 50% higher than the European average, respectively.
On the other hand, thanks to our consistent energy policy, our neighbors pay 40% more for electricity than French households.
As the price of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and the guarantee of maintenance of industrial equipment on the national territory in a globalized economy, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in nuclear power will lead to a large increase in the cost of electricity, which will make the beautiful claims of our country's new industrialization and the protection of purchasing power illusory.
A price that most French people refuse to pay, especially because they have no objection to this type of energy in principle.
It should be recalled that the country's energy policy has made it possible to create an industry with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Strongly export-oriented, it attracts a whole slew of small and medium-sized enterprises specialising in international trade and creates many jobs that cannot be transferred to another industry.
If France were to decide to abandon nuclear energy, it would have to sacrifice a large number of these enterprises and lose 6 billion euros a year from French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrical engineer would order an EPR designed to run for 60 years if the manufacturer was scheduled to shut down?
To solve the energy equation, we must recognize that there are no divine or diabolical sources of energy.
Areva's development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions is a testament to the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest level of security is a vital issue for nuclear energy .
In France, we have a security authority that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing energy centres, such as Flamenville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is universally acknowledged, are filled with the same obsession with safety.
In 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three major accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions, but without any human or environmental impact.
At Chernobyl, the reactor's design and an unforgivable human error led to tragedy.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented strength that claimed tens of thousands of lives.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did from the two before.
The result of this step and cooperation between security agencies, operators and French and German designers, EPR, is a project that allows us to confront such phenomena.
Since it is considered by all energy professionals who wish to build a reactor, the halt in its construction in Flamenville would be a great gift to Areva and EDF's competitors, paving the way for them to take the lead in the inevitable development of nuclear energy.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best combination of energy sources for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotions, dogmas and biased maneuvers to prevail in a dispute that is so important to our country's economic, social and financial status.
Immigration - Burden or Benefit for the Economy?
The immigration policy of Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various quarters - overloading the police, judicial and administrative services, subordinated to the politics of numbers and the compatibility of this policy with France's self-proclaimed status as a "human rights state".
Then there was the administrative harassment of foreign students, which made headlines when the Minister of the Interior (Liberation, May 23) declared that France "did not need foreign talents, stonemasons and waiters".
But it's rarely analyzed from an economic perspective.
Right and left are in agreement on a lot of things.
The right-wing was set by Jacques Chirac, who in 1976 declared that "900,000 unemployed people will not be a problem in a country with 2 million foreign workers", and the left-wing was set by Michel Rocard, who in 1990 explained that France "cannot accept poor people from all over the world".
The difference is in the level of generosity.
In 2005, both the left and the right felt the fear of invasion of the country by the hordes of Polish water pipelines.
Both sides see immigration as a burden on the French economy and on French society.
The only difference is the level of generosity they're willing to show to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande limited himself to the trivia, saying that "working together will solve our immigration problem".
This view of immigration as a burden and a problem can provide an electoral advantage, but it is very costly economically.
As economists Ian Goldin and Jeffrey Cameron remind us in their recent book summarizing recent immigration data (Special People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Determine Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pages), there is broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries that receive immigrants.
Restricting immigration leads to weaker growth and lower employment.
Fears of the influence of immigrants are based on the notion that they can replace local workers, especially those with low skills, by provoking lower wages.
But experience shows that in reality, immigrants are far more complementary than replacement for the local workforce, doing jobs for which the local workforce is lacking.
The unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract local labour, and the most skilled immigrants work in dynamic sectors where training is not linked to job offers.
Positive impact on salaries
Just as it would be difficult for a surgeon to work in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, the complementarity between locals and immigrants means that the influx of immigrants has a positive impact on the wages of local workers.
Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in the migration flow leads to a 0.6-0.9% increase in real long-term wages.
And that's without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants creates new ideas and economic growth (there are a large proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel Prize winners, and Google, Intel, Paypal and Yahoo were all founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net income to the social security system, contributing on average 1% of the total budgets of European countries.
The World Labor Organization estimates that, for example, in Germany, an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will bring an average of EUR 150 000 in net income (income minus expenses) to the state budget over his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy, at the beginning of his term, was going to "tooth" the missing points of growth.
The teeth used to scare off immigrants had the exact opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, it remains to understand European democracy
Democracy is a valuable asset; but it is also fragile.
The European continent should remember that, having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, in the 20th century it has survived the tragedies of World War I, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, the Gulag, as well as Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and the colonels in Greece.
Some believed that for democracy to finally triumph over its enemies, it was enough to arrange the vote and make it as direct as possible.
We've known since Napoleon the Younger that it comes from the surface of thinking.
The universal vote, while a necessary condition of democracy, is not a sufficient condition and may even become "an instrument of repression", as the republican philosopher Etienne Vashko once said.
No, democracy requires much more: public space, public spirit, values, organization, division and control of power, education, education, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The European crisis we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is first and foremost a political crisis and a crisis of democracy.
In this respect, the palinody of the true-false Greek referendum will have a double exposing effect, demonstrating both the need for a serious policy change and the unpleasant feeling of its impossibility and inconsistency.
This duality needs to be understood to overcome it.
The truth is that the front line of the fight for democracy has shifted now, and many believe that the Republican soldiers are now aiming in the wrong direction.
We won't win anything by demanding a series of national referendums, organized as needed and in a chaotic order.
A carte blanche for an absolute European monarch or a bound leg jump into the abyss of nationalism - what a choice for a citizen!
No, we do not dream of a guillotine blade, but of the implementation - joint, clear and continuous - of choice and democracy, this time at the European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal, and I don't know how many more I have to list, because there is only one crisis, the crisis of Europe.
The whole of Europe is subject to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, suffering from its own weakness and lack of solidarity.
The whole of Europe is humiliated on the international stage.
Many are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but Europe as a whole is gradually losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
It is urgent to return the management of the European project to the people's sovereignty.
Because only by working together can Europeans reduce the burden of each other's debts, free themselves from markets and prepare for the future by investing in it.
The way out of the crisis will require solutions at the European level, and they cannot be adopted without full democratic legitimacy, without leading us to disaster.
After a long discussion of this proposal, the socialists and Jacques Delors are now demanding a European economic government.
Let's have it.
But to imagine it without the stronger economic, political and democratic integration that has been achieved by citizens is another madness and a new deadlock.
We must start a new phase of European construction.
To establish a republic in France, it was necessary to "create" republicans.
A revolution of interest would not be enough.
That lesson is still valid.
We must build an economically united Europe.
This can only be done by creating a more democratic Europe at the political level, a real European people's sovereignty.
To create Europe, let's create the Europeans.
