The terrorist front spreads from the Sahara to Nigeria
Paris is concerned about the Islamic Maghreb's ties to the Boko Haram sect.
Long-held links between the Al-Qaeda terrorist group in the Muslim Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Boko Haram sect in Nigeria have been confirmed.
On Sunday, the deputy foreign minister of Algeria, Abdelkader Messaghel, even stated that Algerians are now confident.
"The way these two organizations are doing it, and the intelligence reports, show that they are actively cooperating", he explained, without going into details.
Paris seems to have come to the same conclusion.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger in January has revealed two links.
Abducted from a restaurant in Niamey by people close to Aqmi, Antoine de Lecourt and Vincent Delory were apparently killed the next day along with several of the kidnappers during an operation conducted by French special forces.
Among the debris left over from the operation, French and Nigerian investigators found several phone SIM cards belonging to the terrorists.
The axis of terror
Analysis of the calls indicated several interlocutors in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), investigators are particularly interested in two numbers; one points to a Nigerian who has lived for a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man allegedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
"This is a step forward, but we must certainly wait for more solid evidence before we talk about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram".
"But it is possible".
"It has been known for years that the sect receives financial and ideological support from outside and that it is becoming more and more active", says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
