The international community, led by Washington, is now pressuring Abuja to address the problems being created by Boko Haram.
The fact is, the Nigerian authorities have traditionally viewed this group as a community of educated people who are not interested.
Fast success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri by a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist imam Mohammed Youssef, Boko Haram - which in Hausa means "Western education is a sin" - preaches the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the organization has achieved rapid success.
It is politicised and demands strict Sharia law, and its activists have begun a struggle against the corrupt central government.
