Nord Stream, the new gateway for Russian gas to Europe.
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, connecting Western Europe and Russia directly under the Baltic Sea, has been launched.
It's designed to supply the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, Russia's giant gas producer, wanted to celebrate with a pump.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, attended last Tuesday on the shores of the Baltic Sea, between a performance by the orchestra and a fine snack, the opening of the Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia and Germany underwater.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mart Rütte have together turned the symbolic valve that controls the flow of Russian gas into the Western European network.
The new pipeline will provide 27,5 million cubic meters of gas to Western Europe each year through the first pipeline, which will connect the Leningrad region with the Meklenburg-Pomeranian region.
The second pipeline is due to be completed by the end of 2012, providing a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, equivalent to the entire consumption of France.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline in the same direction is already being discussed.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project is a victory.
The project met with fierce resistance from Poland and the Baltic states.
Nord Stream will actually allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries will lose some of their power: they will find it harder to influence Russia, threatening to shut down access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not stop at comparing the North Stream with the new "German-Soviet Pact", hinting at an alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That means it's politically sensitive.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe is seeking greater security of its supplies.
But at the cost of Europe's energy deficit, because the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europe.
Russia has managed in less than five years to achieve its understanding of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which consume large volumes of gas and whose own reserves are already running out.
"This gas pipeline is part of the cooperation with Russia, it is a new artery that organically connects us", argued François Fillon, opening the pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which large gas contracts are important both politically and economically.
All this explains the broad smiles on the faces of the heads of Gazprom, who were present in large numbers in Lubmin, the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is a technical feat.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel, encased in concrete to protect it from ship anchors.
It lies on the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 meters.
To build it, we had to bypass the minefields left over from World War II.
"The stink had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution", said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
Many steps were also needed to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipeline is a long metal snake weighing as much as 242 Eiffel Towers, with no gaps along its length, no valves, and no service stations.
The control platform was planned in the area of Sweden, but the project managers rejected it because Sweden was not thrilled that the Russian state-owned company would permanently settle on its shores.
"In the event of an accident, we can shut down the gas flow in less than a minute", says Jens Müller.
So if there's a leak, the gas in the pipeline will be released into the air.
But that seems unlikely to designers who have designed seams designed to only leak once every 100,000 years.
The gas pipeline will be monitored by an underwater robot that pulls the ship for external observation, as well as by a device that circulates inside the pipeline.
The cigar-shaped apparatus is inserted into a 1 meter diameter pipe and pushed forward by a gas stream.
Upon arrival after 3 full days of travel at 3 meters per second, it gives accurate information on any deformation of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to run for 50 years without the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is only done by its pressure.
It's 200 bars on the way out and 100 bars on the way in.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which owns 51% of the capital.
The rest are German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), Dutch Gasunie and French Group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies formed a joint venture called North Stream, which was charged with building and operating the pipeline.
Its headquarters are in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Then Gazprom leased it to this company for 20 years with the option of extending the entire volume of gas transportation.
"Gazprom will pay for the full volume, regardless of how much gas is actually transported", says Jens Müller.
The gas pipeline was financed by 30% shareholders and 70% bank loans.
The total cost of the works will be 7.4 thousand million euros for two pipelines.
The investment of GDF Suez will be about 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are confident they'll recoup their costs because Gazprom takes all the risks.
The gas pipeline runs from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin to a sandy shore, planted with conifers.
The 4.5 meter high valves form the gas outlet.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas before it is pumped into German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of gas every hour.
