The Moleskine brand notebook
Moleskine, created by an Italian company 15 years ago, will bring back the taste for writing.
It has the smell of adventure, hours spent writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable by its rectangular black cover, by the rubber, by the yellowish-white pages that appear to have turned yellow over time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born in 1997.
Modo Modo, an Italian company based in Milan, decided to launch a designer notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, took responsibility for launching the new product.
The note is inspired by the old production technique, moleskin - a lacquered cotton fabric used, for example, to cover benches.
It is said that this type of notebook is highly prized by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine brought to life an old and forgotten thing that was a cult for avant-garde artists until the 20th century", said Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success has come.
From 2006 to 2010, sales increased by 25% and reached 12.7 million units.
We've come a long way from the early years, when only 3,000 notebooks were produced.
Moleskine has crossed the borders of Italy and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It's hard to profile a typical buyer because the notebook attracts businessmen, students, and freelancers alike.
Moleskine's customers are cosmopolitan, broad-minded, and educated.
A small Italian company that started with only 12 employees now has 100 and two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in Fnac bookstores, small shops in the centers of small towns and has been able to gain wide recognition.
"We followed the spirit of the times and this new need for correspondence, despite the advent of e-mail", explains Maria Sebregondi.
This distinctive cultural trait has accompanied the development of Moleskine; the brand recently organized the "Round the Way" exhibition, where architects and artists showcased their own notebooks.
In August, he also launched a leopard cover for the Locarno Film Festival.
Using its success and cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products, which now include bags, pens, computer bags, and all kinds of support.
A success that aroused envy: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, which wrote a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate among disabled workers so high?
Approximately 19% of disabled people are looking for work.
The 15th week of employment for the disabled begins today.
Despite a public charity policy launched in 2005, the unemployment rate among the disabled is still twice the average, at 19%, compared to 9% for the general population.
Discouraging you?
"No", says Eric Blanche, CEO of Adapt, an organization that organizes Disability Employment Week.
"In 15 years, significant progress has been made".
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not two times higher, but three times higher".
"But there is still much work to be done".
I must say that there are still many obstacles to employment for the disabled.
Among them , there are more elderly: 37% over 50 years old (average 17%).
They are more of a low-skilled population: 80% do not have a bachelor's degree, and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, there is a very high prevalence of long-term unemployment, which is 85% for people with disabilities versus 38% on average.
In short, these are criteria that make it very difficult to return to work and that are the heart of the problem", says Christian Grapen, CEO of Tremplin, an association set up in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There's no need to talk about a mentality that's changing, but it's changing too slowly.
A study commissioned by Cité and conducted in April by IMS-Entreprendre found that managers had low levels of disability knowledge and "imagined themselves as solid people in wheelchairs or mentally or mentally handicapped".
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from the target of having 6% disabled employees set out in the 1987 law.
The latest known figures for 2008 are 2.6%.
"Today we are at about 3 percent", says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, an organization responsible for collecting taxes from companies that do not comply with the law.
Evidence: the number of 'taxable' organisations, as well as the amounts paid, decreased in 2007-2011 from 59 000 to 46 000 organisations (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 tax law put a lot of pressure on the companies", explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects the growing awareness, particularly in large enterprises".
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of organizations with 20 to 49 employees have disabled employees, compared to 82% of organizations with 100 to 199 employees.
